name: PIER 39
opening_hours: ['Monday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 9:00 PM']
reviews:
[['oscar johnson', 5, 'This is a very fun place to visit as a tourist. You can actually get good food. The farmers market has wonderful fresh local  fruits. I personally like Wipe Out for a tropical themed drink. Chowders has great clay chowder in a bread bowl.

Great shops with a good selection of gifts.

Great place to people watch (and also Sea Lion watch). There is definitely an amusement park feel here. At the end of Fisherman's Wharf it is part of what makes "The City" memorable.'], ['randee deason', 4, "I'm not a tourist anymore and I don't visit anymore that often. Pier 39 is still a destination spot that does not disappoint. I was here twice this past week ,once a Monday and then again on a Saturday. The Monday was almost a ghost town from what I have seen in years past and Saturday appeared to be full operation. My kids really enjoyed themselves watching the sea lions, food, merry go round and another thrill ride as we shared our family time entertaining an out of town guest. Do it, just do it, enjoy the enthusiastic scene of street performers and the shopping Pier 39 has to offer."], ['Paul Overstreet', 5, "What a great experience!  1st time visiting the piers and although it is certainly a tourist trap, the endless amount of places to eat fresh seafood is awesome. They also of course have some very talented street acts worth your time to stop and watch (don't forget to leave a tip if you can). Would love to come back as my wife and I are not from San Francisco and eat at as much seafood as we can. Beautiful views."], ['Mori', 5, "Love Pier 39 - tons of shops to check out and probably one of the best Lids store you'll find is right here at Pier 39. There are quite a few restaurants to choose from and a couple of coffee shops as well. We spent a solid 2 hours in this area and enjoyed every minute. We were there pretty early so there wasn't much of a crowd, but once it got closer to 11am, the crowd started rolling in and it was bustling. If you're visiting the SF area, I highly recommend coming here."], ['Emily Arbec', 5, 'I’ve been here multiple times as a tourist and every single time it’s just a great place to go and do anything, really! Made tons of good memories. I just love it every time when we come. I definitely recommend this place... especially the candy shop! I was in HEAVEN!']]

[['Quaranteam', 5, 'The\xa0Golden Gate Bridge\xa0is a\xa0suspension bridge\xa0spanning the\xa0Golden Gate, the one-mile-wide (1.6\xa0km)\xa0strait\xa0connecting\xa0San Francisco Bay\xa0and the\xa0Pacific Ocean. The structure links the U.S. city of\xa0San Francisco,\xa0California—the northern tip of the\xa0San Francisco Peninsula—to\xa0Marin County, carrying both\xa0U.S. Route 101\xa0and\xa0California State Route 1\xa0across the strait. The bridge is one of the most internationally recognized symbols of San Francisco and California. It was initially designed by engineer\xa0Joseph Strauss\xa0in 1917. It has been declared one of the\xa0Wonders of the Modern World\xa0by the\xa0American Society of Civil Engineers.
Just beautiful ❤️'], ['Nirmala Pajaniradja', 5, "The vista point is a best place to watch the golden gate from different angles. Usually the parking lot is full. But if we try to move slowly inside the parking lot, people might leave and u might get a spot. It's pure LUCK ;)

The restrooms are clean. You can meet people from different cultures, cities and ethnics and this is one of the super popular touristic spot in San Francisco. Enjoy this beauty :)"], ['Vijay Vikram Verma', 5, 'This Beautiful place is situated in San Francisco in California state.as name it is like gate of gold.
The Golden Gate Bridge is a suspension bridge spanning the Golden Gate, the one-mile-wide (1.6 km) strait connecting San Francisco Bay and the Pacific Ocean. The structure links the U.S. city of San Francisco, California—the northern tip of the San Francisco Peninsula—to Marin County, carrying both U.S. Route 101 and California State Route 1 across the strait. The bridge is one of the most internationally recognized symbols of San Francisco and California. It was initially designed by engineer Joseph Strauss in 1917. It has been declared one of the Wonders of the Modern World by the American Society of Civil Engineers.
This place is amazing you have to see it at least once in lifetime.'], ['Amelia May', 5, 'We parked at the very end of Crissy Field parking lot. Walked the 0.8 easy walk up to the Golden Gate Bridge. Not very crowded. Weather was phenomenal for late October. Views were stunning of the San Francisco skyline, Alcatraz and so much more. A definite must do while San Francisco.'], ['Glen G', 5, 'A beautiful world destination! The Holden Gate Bridge is majestic in its presence and beauty. If you’re in the area don’t miss it. There’s a wonderful visitor center, cafe and information area. Plus, you can walk the bridge... truly a California treasure and a world destination.']]

description:
The Golden Gate Bridge is a suspension bridge spanning the Golden Gate, the one-mile-wide (1.6 km) strait connecting San Francisco Bay and the Pacific Ocean. The structure links the U.S. city of San Francisco, California—the northern tip of the San Francisco Peninsula—to Marin County, carrying both U.S. Route 101 and California State Route 1 across the strait. It also carries pedestrian and bicycle traffic, and is designated as part of U.S. Bicycle Route 95. Being declared one of the Wonders of the Modern World by the American Society of Civil Engineers,[7] the bridge is one of the most internationally recognized symbols of San Francisco and California. It was initially designed by engineer Joseph Strauss in 1917.
The Frommer's travel guide describes the Golden Gate Bridge as "possibly the most beautiful, certainly the most photographed, bridge in the world."[8][9] At the time of its opening in 1937, it was both the longest and the tallest suspension bridge in the world, with a main span of 4,200 feet (1,280 m) and a total height of 746 feet (227 m).[10]

name: Golden Gate Park
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['Betty Merrill', 5, 'Such an amazing space. There is something for everyone inside the leafy green boundaries of Golden Gate Park. Understand that you cannot see it all in one day. Choose your activities carefully and plan your transportation ahead of time. There are numerous free spaces with no fees. But there are a few attractions you simply must see. The Academy of Sciences and Japanese Tea Gardens are two I highly recommend. Try for 1 pm at the Tea Garden and look for the free tour provided by the SF Library.'], ['Angie Gorkoff', 5, "Spacious park with ample free parking everywhere. Lots to see, lots of benches to rest on. Park is very well kept. Different theme areas that are very well organized. Eateries and bathrooms are strangely non-existent in most places which isn't good and the reason we couldn't stay longer. Definitely need several days to explore even a small part of this massive park."], ['Mark McHugh', 5, "The botanical gardens are worth the little price for admission. Lakes, ponds, trees, plants and flowers, from all over the world. Anytime of year. Spring best. Tulip season is only 2 weeks but it's amazing! Usually late March, but weather dictates. March 22, 2022 is perfect!"], ['M Yorke', 5, 'Nice park for a walk, bike ride or picnic. It was well maintained and clean, with good toilet facilities. We walked most of it, but there was a free bus. At the pacific end there was a good restaurant and the beach area was nice to sunbathe on (clean). You could probably do a full day here; we did half a day, and really enjoyed it.'], ['Dawn Beard', 5, "I ALWAYS visit Golden Gate Park when I come to the city. There is so much to see when you walk around, and you can't do it all in one day. The people watching is wonderful. Just a gorgeous, peaceful place to go!"]]

description:
Golden Gate Park, located in San Francisco, California, United States, is a large urban park consisting of 1,017 acres (412 ha) of public grounds. It is administered by the San Francisco Recreation & Parks Department, which began in 1871 to oversee the development of Golden Gate Park. Configured as a rectangle, it is similar in shape to but 20 percent larger than Central Park in New York City, to which it is often compared. It is over three miles (4.8 km) long east to west, and about half a mile (0.8 km) north to south.[3] With 24 million visitors annually, Golden Gate is the third most-visited city park in the United States after Central Park and the Lincoln Memorial.[1][4]
In the 1860s, San Franciscans began to feel the need for a spacious public park similar to Central Park, which was then taking shape in New York City. Golden Gate Park was carved out of unpromising sand and shore dunes that were known as the Outside Lands, in an unincorporated area west of San Francisco's then-current borders. In 1865, Frederick Law Olmsted proposed a plan for a park using native species suited for San Francisco's dry climate; however, the proposal was rejected in favor of a Central Park-style park needing extensive irrigation.[5] Conceived ostensibly for recreation, the underlying purpose of the park was housing development and the westward expansion of the city. The tireless field engineer William Hammond Hall prepared a survey and topographic map of the park site in 1870 and became its commissioner in 1871. He was later named California's first state engineer and developed an integrated flood control system for the Sacramento Valley. The park drew its name from the nearby Golden Gate Strait.

reviews:
[['Millie Kwan', 5, "This is a great place to see the Golden Gate Bridge! The view is great since you can see the bridge span the opening of the bay. Also the fort is fun to look around and the location makes sense as a point of defense. We went on a fairly windy and cool day so if that's the case when you're visiting, bring a coat or at least a wind breaker. Great national historic site and worth the visit."], ['Ibrahim J', 4, 'Lower view of golden gate bridge and a far view of alcatraz.'], ['Evan Davis', 5, "The fort is back open so we went in for a walk around the battlements. There's not a lot to this place, but the stuff there is is interesting. See the cannons, cannonballs, quarters, and of course great views of the bottom of the Golden Gate Bridge. The railing is there and functional, but it was built in a time where shorter was good enough. Jerome the French teacher'], ['James Baker', 5, "We went on a Friday afternoon, the fort was open. There are breath taking views of the Golden Gate bridge. The fort itself is very well maintained and there are a lot of interesting displays to read. The only down side is that there is way too much emphasis on the Buffalo Soldiers in the fort. Good info on the lighthouse. The rangers were very friendly and helpful. There was no admission to enter the fort and parking was free. It was a little walk to the fort but not too bad. Note to all it's windy in the fort so dress for it. Even with the sun out it's cold as the wind comes off the Pacific Ocean. The best views were from the top of the fort so be sure to make your way up there. Overall a great place to spend an afternoon."]]

description:
The fort was completed just before the American Civil War by the United States Army, to defend San Francisco Bay against hostile warships. The fort is now protected as Fort Point National Historic Site, a United States National Historic Site administered by the National Park Service as a unit of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area. It is now popular as a tourist viewing point of the Golden Gate Bridge directly alongside it.
In 1769 Spain occupied the San Francisco area and by 1776 had established the area's first European settlement, with a mission and a presidio. To protect against encroachment by the British and Russians, Spain selected Punta del Cantil Blanco, a promontory with a high white cliff (cantil blanco) located at the narrowest part of the bay's entrance,[4] to construct a fortification.  The Castillo de San Joaquin was constructed in 1794, subordinate to the nearby Presidio de San Francisco.  It was an adobe structure housing nine to thirteen cannons.[5]

name: Lands End Lookout
opening_hours: ['Monday: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Tuesday: Closed', 'Wednesday: Closed', 'Thursday: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Friday: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Andrew Litwiller', 5, "This may be my favorite place in SF. So beautiful, and so peaceful. There's a great hiking trail that will take you north about a mile and half. If you go a bit further, you can get to China Beach or Baker Beach.

Lands End is also located right next to Ocean Beach (neighboring to the south), and is accessible via the light rail muni or the bus. It isn't always sunny and warm in this part of the city, but when it is, it doesn't get any better. Great views of the ocean, and interesting scenery all around. Also, great trails to wander about. There are also a few good restaurants nearby, although I usually pack a lunch when I head out there. Well worth the trek!"], ['Millie Kwan', 5, 'Interesting historic park with great views of the ocean and the city of San Francisco. The store has some interesting facts about the area as a public bath area. The walk down is fairly easy. The parking lot is large but there are warnings about not leaving valuables in view so take precautions. A fun visit and worth a trip.'], ['Alexander Hernandez', 5, 'Great urban decay, one of San Francisco’s treasures'], ['Jay Shah', 5, "Probably one of the most accessible and beautiful viewpoints of the golden gate bridge plus the SF Bay. The trail is very mild and easy to follow, although be warned there is almost no signage so you'll have to follow google maps on your phone. We also went down to the rocky beach area which gave us a great view of the waves crashing against the rocks. Overall highly recommend."], ['Brinda Guru', 5, 'The lands end lookout point offers beautiful views of the ocean and the surrounding baths. The lands end trail is beautiful, relaxing, and offers amazing views of the Golden Gate Bridge. It is super close to the city, family friendly and accessible for elders too!

The best hike in the city! 🤩']]

reviews:
[['Quincy Ess', 5, "Union Square is a clean, well lit, and nicely decorated square in San Francisco, surrounded by high end shopping and a few restaurants. It's well stocked with trash cans and seating areas for the public. There are adequate security guards to keep the area safe and calm. Teenagers, tourists, and locals alike can all enjoy the space. It's great for what it is."], ['Hamilton Jimenez Vasquez', 3, 'Right now everything is pretty limited there, with a lot of things under construction'], ['J why', 5, 'Nike Store..... #3&#4......'], ['KARTIK YADAV', 4, 'Union square, being one of the major city Center attractions in San Francisco has a lot to offer. From malls, eateries to ice rink and more fun games, this place has it all. ✨ This place is packed with fun.
Union square is mostly crowded, even more during evenings and night time. 💃
This place has some really great eateries to grab quick bites and to dine as well.
Union square is wheelchair accessible.
Can be a little confusing for first time visitors; don’t worry Google Maps has your back. 😂

You can easily expect to spend 2-3 hours here or more, depending upon your activities.

There are some budget shops to get souvenirs too.. (CVS Pharmacy & more)
Union square has a lit vibe with so much to do, and also their are several (small) live musical shows that take place.
Preferable time to visit would be evenings to savour the city lights.
Macy’s is one more highlight of Union Square.
Buses/ trams are easily available here in frequent time intervals, the connectivity is a plus.

Would suggest walking around, as it helps, explore the square with more detail.'], ['Rebecca Gorzell (Persephone)', 5, "The shopping! Very nice selection of stores if you are in the mood. I had a destination in mind. Louis Vuitton. Nice store. It's quite a busy area but you can find very nice stores. Chanel, Gucci, Tory Burch to name a few. Sometimes there's sea lions that poke around."], ['Kim McBride', 5, 'Fun and very educational.  It is self guiding but it is worth the admission price to help support our parks and museums.  If you live in the San Francisco area take some time and go support your local park and the economy.  If you plan to visit San Francisco plan to visit this great place.'], ['Ken Landry', 4, 'Views are great. Please come prepared for a cool or cold wind. It can be quite breezy here. name: Aquarium of the Bay
address: PIER 39 The Embarcadero &, Beach St, San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Thursday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Friday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Saturday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Sunday: 11:00 AM – 6:00 PM']
reviews:
[['KARTIK YADAV', 5, "A lovely aquarium. Most of the negative reviews seem to be an issue of expectations. It's small, yes, and you could easily see everything in an hour if you don't linger much. But you could also spend several hours peacefully watching the fish and other critters. The largest animals are some small (nurse?) sharks, probably about 4 to 5 ft in length. Lots of colorful colorful fish and very cute otters. The touching pools were also a cool unique feature."], ['R', 5, 'Wonderful place to visit with family and friends to see a great variety of marine life and learn more about our oceans.

Their displays are some of the best I have ever seen.

The staff is friendly and helpful, super nice to kids too. I remember :)

Bathrooms are clean and easy to find.

Parking isn’t easy but you can get here using public transport quite easily.

Great places to eat all around the area.'], ['Jewel Weed', 5, "Went here as a child and absolutely love it. Came back 11 years later and loved it just the same. Although it was a little confusing walking around. It was still very pleasant to go. My favorite is the tunnel. I'm glad it's still there. I can't wait to go back and enjoy it again. ❤️"], ['Benjamin Etgen', 4, "Small kids raced through the aquarium in a few minutes during our visit. Older kids are more impressed with the diversity of dish including rays and sharks. For an adult the lack of signage is disappointing. I didn't learn much but I really enjoyed seeing how much life there should be under the waves. The River Otters appear happy in a reasonably large enclosure. They are bright curious animals and fun to watch. You can take a #39 bus up to Coit Tower every 20 minutes until 7:00 pm to get a view and rest your legs."], ['austin ramirez', 1, '100% would not recommend to anyone who has to pay for this. While the exhibits they did have were cool, there just was not enough to be worth the price. What seemed to be a quick walk of 3 rooms and a tunnel was not what we were expecting. Very underwhelming and will not be coming back. I would recommend going to another aquarium for a better experience. For a total of $60 to walk for maybe 45 minutes is not good. There was 2 floors that employees would not verify is there used to be more exhibits. In any event it was very underwhelming and not a good experience. If you examine every rock in every tank maybe it’s over an hour but not as a normal walk. The tunnel was the best part but after that it was nothing to be excited about. Having come from Sacramento to get this experience was terribly saddening. We go all over to zoos and aquariums and this just was not up to par. The SF zoo is a must see but this aquarium is a no go. Would not recommend. Deeply disappointed to the point nobody wanted to get souvenirs because we don’t want to remember this trip to this place. 👎']]

description:
Aquarium of the Bay is a public aquarium located at The Embarcadero and Beach Street, at the edge of Pier 39 in San Francisco, California. The aquarium is focused on local aquatic animals from the San Francisco Bay and neighboring rivers and watersheds as far as the Sierra Mountains. 
Since 2005 the Aquarium has focused its mission on enabling ocean conservation and climate action both locally and globally. It is one of seven institutions under parent company Bay Ecotarium, the largest watershed conservation organization in the Bay Area
The Aquarium of the Bay is a Smithsonian Affiliate, accredited by Association of Zoos and Aquariums (AZA) and certified as a Green Business by the city of San Francisco. It contains over 750,000 gallons of salt water that over 24,000 animals from 200+ species call home. It is the only Smithsonian-affiliated aquarium in the state of California.

description:
In 2013, Merlin Entertainments signed a lease with the Wax Museum at Fishermans Wharf  to transform the venue into both the Madame Tussauds wax attraction and the San Francisco Dungeon. The Wax Museum had operated for 50 years and had over 270 wax figures.[1]

name: San Francisco Botanical Garden
opening_hours: ['Monday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Thursday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Friday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Saturday: 7:30 AM – 7:00 PM', 'Sunday: 7:30 AM – 6:00 PM']
reviews: [['Keith Boyea', 5, "One of the most pleasant places I've ever been. The sequoia trees were incredible. California, it's just so blessed with natural beauty. Another brilliant thing to note was how many foreign visitors were here. I love that! Getting to share an experience with people from all over is divine."], ['Ryan H', 5, "Wonderful garden! I came in November so not a whole lot of flowers but I can only imagine what peak bloom season looks like! Plenty of places to relax and secluded spots to meditate or read a book. Plus for SF residents entrance is free, which I am not but not many gardens do that. So if you live here, lucky you! If I'm ever back in the summer, I'll be back!"], ['Mark Dulac', 5, "This is a very large botanical garden in Golden Gate park. It covers many parts of the globe and has some very large beautiful plants. We loved the prehistoric area, the rhododendrons section and especially the succulent area. Lots of room to spread out and enjoy. Don't forget to see the Redwoods!"], ['Taruna Arora', 5, 'Very beautiful and serene, very calm walking around. Beautiful plants and different types from different places. Nice areas for picnic and enjoy the beauty. We were there in Fall, not much blooming that time, but Thanksgiving is free admission so totally worth it. Will visit again in summer'], ['Rose Florez', 5, 'Lovely place to learn about horticulture from around the world. Interesting butterflies and birds, parts of the park feel like your in another country. Please donate and keep this garden beautiful.\n\nThey also sell flowers and plants at reasonable prices. Great place for families with kids of all ages, no dogs allowed.']]

description:
San Francisco's County Fair Building is located near the main entrance to the Garden.
Plans for the garden were originally laid out in the 1880s by park supervisor John McLaren, but funding was insufficient to begin construction until Helene Strybing left a major bequest in 1927.[4] Planting was begun in 1937 with WPA funds supplemented by local donations, and the Arboretum officially opened in May 1940.[5] As a part of Golden Gate Park, it is officially managed by the city of San Francisco, but the San Francisco Botanical Garden Society plays an important role in providing educational programs, managing volunteers, curatorial staff, and more. Formed in 1955, the San Francisco Botanical Garden Society (formerly the Strybing Arboretum Society) operates the Helen Crocker Russell Library of Horticulture, Garden Bookstore, and monthly plant sales, and offers a wide range of community education programs for children and adults. The Society also raises money for new projects and Garden renovations.

reviews:
[['Ron Plasencia', 5, "This visit was much better than my last one!

The hostess was cordial, and I was seated quickly (although I was put in the far back corner).

Macy was my server and was properly attentive.

Order place, order received,  all good. For this visit I ordered the Millionaires Burger with sweet potato fries.  The hamburger was delicious! It is now on my Top 5 best hamburgers list.  The sweet potato fries were perfectly cooked: crispy on the ootside and tasty!

Side note
I'm a photographer and I had just finished up a photo shoot with a model. Two models that I have photographed work here, so that's why I return.  Neither were on duty this night.

I often eat alone and since I'm driving, I never order drinks.  Perhaps these two factors lead to my usually  receiving adequate to poor service.  Which is too bad since I tip 50% for good service."], ['Heidi Kaden', 5, 'Always a great view of the city when there is no fog rolling through. I think the best views are sunset and sunrise though! Either way if you want to take your out of town friends or family for a short hike with a wonderful stunning view of San Francisco and surrounding area then this is your best bet. You can also catch a glimpse of the magnificent Golden Gate Bridge as well.'], ['J Hunt', 5, 't-pickup late night pizza'], ['Jonathan Dirrenberger', 4, 'Great views, but that means tourists, which can be pretty overwhelming, especially on nice weekend days. Getting rid of cars had made the space much better, though what they really need to do is remove the roads (or at least on one side of the peaks) and replace them with dirt paths. This will get rid of some of the crowd that hangs out up there at night and sprays graffiti and breaks glass everywhere. On that note, the main reason I take away a star on what otherwise is a 5-star SF treasure, is there is broken glass everywhere and graffiti has really gotten worse. The city needs to put more effort into cleaning up and also getting somebody up there at night scaring the vandals away.'], ['Julia Bennet', 5, 'One of the "Go To" spots if you really want to impress someone who is new to San Francisco and wants to enjoy a great view in a city full of great views. If you have an afternoon off, even hiking up the hill is kind of fun to enjoy a great view payoff at the end. Can get chilly towards evening especially if the fog is rolling in. Carry a jacket. description:
Twin Peaks is an American mystery serial drama television series created by Mark Frost and David Lynch. It premiered on ABC on April 8, 1990, and originally ran for two seasons until its cancellation in 1991. In the years following its release, the show gained a devoted cult following and has been referenced in a wide variety of media.[4][5][6][7] Twin Peaks is often listed among the greatest television series of all time, and has received universal acclaim from critics and audiences. It is considered a landmark turning point in television drama.[8][9][10][11][12]
The series follows an investigation, headed by FBI Special Agent Dale Cooper (Kyle MacLachlan) and local Sheriff Harry S. Truman (Michael Ontkean), into the murder of homecoming queen Laura Palmer (Sheryl Lee) in the fictional town of Twin Peaks, Washington. The show's narrative draws on elements of detective fiction, but its uncanny tone, supernatural elements, and campy, melodramatic portrayal of eccentric characters also draws from American soap opera and horror tropes.[13][14][7][15] Like much of Lynch's work, it is distinguished by surrealism, offbeat humor, and distinctive cinematography.[16] The score was composed by Angelo Badalamenti with Lynch.[17]

name: Sutro Baths
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['Ann 916', 5, "It's a long way down the sandy and dirt-covered wood stairs so wear shoes with good soles. It's not safe for young children or adventurous young teens so monitor your brood well. To the right of the bath ruins is a cave with the ocean waters crashing through. Wet sand inside, dark, and there is a low metal small fence that blocks people from jumping over ... but very little. Easy jump over and then to then to slip on the rocks down below. Bring a rope!  There is no lifeguard around so be careful.\nCan't get into the gift store without a mask. Restrooms on outside of gift store. Parking is easy."], ['Maeg Berkowitz', 5, 'Beautiful piece of recent history. This bath house was active until the 1960’s at which time it was going to be turned to a skating rink. The rink never happened and the building was severely damaged by fire. This is a little slice of heaven on the cusp of the city. Lands end neighbors this site and compliments it well with some great easy hiking. Great for all ages'], ['A M B', 5, "I can only imagine how beautiful this place was in its heyday. Loved the walking trails to get to the bottom and around the baths.  Lots of remnants to see. The cave with the blow hole is impressive. If you look closely, there's rock out in the sea with a heart in the center."], ['Cody Morgott', 5, 'Amazing location with so much history. If you visit make sure you go into the cave and catch the view from the end pretty awesome. Also recommend stopping by the visitors center for a free tour to see pictures of what this amazing place looked'], ['Alaina Boys', 5, 'Very interesting to explore. Quiet during the week - only a few folks were out. I would imagine it would be much busier on the weekends. Few things to note: The visitor center is closed during chunks of the week, meaning no bathrooms until Ocean Beach. Plan ahead. The whole area within the Baths area is very steep and can be quite slippery. Sneakers / hiking boots and comfortable hiking clothing are recommended, also taking care in slippery areas. Children should be under supervision at all times due to the dangerous nature of the location. Regardless, neat spot to explore on a day off for sure!']]

description:
The Sutro Baths was a large, privately owned public saltwater swimming pool complex in the Lands End area of the Outer Richmond District in western San Francisco, California.[1][2]
Built in 1894, the Sutro Baths was located north of Ocean Beach, the Cliff House, Seal Rocks, and west of Sutro Heights Park.[1] The structure burned down to its concrete foundation in June 1966; its ruins are located in the Golden Gate National Recreation Area and the Sutro Historic District.[3]

name: Coit Tower
opening_hours: ['Monday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Larry Willis', 4, 'Neat place to visit. $10/person to take the elevator to the top. The elevator is original to the building (1933), interesting enough. The elevator comes with an operator (nice guy) and holds about 5 passengers at a time, so it can take a while if things are pretty busy. The views at the top are, of course, quite nice. The top of the tower is open air but the viewing  area is all covered with windows that you look though. It's an interesting place to visit but not a "must see" kind of place. The grounds around the tower are quite nice as well to explore. There are murals and other things to see at the bottom of the tower.'], ['KARTIK YADAV', 5, 'Tower gave beautiful view you can see everything from there! I paid $10 to go upstairs but i felt not worth going up. Its a tiny tower but it gives beautiful view! You can see golden gate, Alcatraz and the downtown! I was expecting a little more, there are glasses by the window and the outer part of the tower is not open! I was expecting that to be open, it would be worth if that space was open. The tower is not too high!!
Great views from the observation area at the top. Very photogenic on a clear day. Alcatraz, the Financial District, Golden Gate Bridge, etc. Can all be seen. Cool experience. Not much to do there once you take photos If the line to the top is quick you may be in and out very quick. Not a lot of parking in the lot below.'], ['Joel Twentyman', 3, "This sixty four metres tall tower was completed in nineteen thirty three and commands an iconic over seeing perspective of San Francisco. Gazing out at its panoramic views, one may be struck by the encroaching grey concrete architectural rash of the city as it seems to creep ever outwards over earth's natural green papillary dermis. A pleasant and redeeming contrast to this sad imposition on the environment can be observed by viewing fine painted murals within the structure which instead reflect an aesthetically higher dimension of mankind's creativity!"], ['Robert Cunningham', 5, "What a beautiful slice of San Francisco and Americana. The murals inside are worth a trip all by themselves. Take a minute and look at the people overturning the car in the intersection or the line of workers by the dam. Pretty inspiring stuff. What about the butcher?
The views are outstanding other than the partial blocking by trees. Also a great walk from almost anywhere in the city if you don't have to drive.
For $10 you can go to the top of the tower and spend as much time as you want getting unobstructed views of the entire area."], ['Thomas Bartlett', 5, "This tower is magical at night. It was closed so we didn't go up to the top, but one can still look out from any direction. And see a beautiful view. I saw the Oakland bridge all lit up, the Golden gate bridge on the other side (unfortunately not lit up), Alcatraz, a really cool looking Church, and many other curious sights. The trees and grass area around the Coit Tower make it a great place to relax and meditate a bit."]]

description:
The art deco tower, built of unpainted reinforced concrete, was designed by architects Arthur Brown, Jr. and Henry Howard. The interior features fresco murals in the American fresco mural painting style, painted by 25 different onsite artists and their numerous assistants, plus two additional paintings installed after creation offsite.
Also known as the Coit Memorial Tower, it was dedicated to the volunteer firemen who had died in San Francisco's five major fires.[3] Although an apocryphal story claims that the tower was designed to resemble a fire hose nozzle[4] due to Coit's affinity with the San Francisco firefighters of the day, the resemblance is coincidental.[5]

reviews:
[['Ernie Saavedra', 5, 'I just happened to be there when the naked bike run was setting up. Its beautiful to see people naked. The human body was not meant to hide. People of all shapes and sizes. I just hope they wore sunblock. Anyway the fresh fruit and atmosphere is always great. Cowgirl creamery cheese is closed. Bummer.'], ['elviscilla2', 5, 'Nice place to visit. Inside the building are lots of local food shops and artists selling their items. Some food lines can be long and prices are a bit pricey but still worth checking out. Behind the building is a great view of the bay. You can also easily walk to Pier 39 from here. Go enjoy.'], ['KKD City', 5, 'WE both have loved Saturdays /Farmers Market at the Ferry Plaza for a very long time. Decades.
We ambled up to Blue Bottle and ordered...Then, we went around the corner to wait in a really, really, long line...Yes, they do the famous pour over - and it is fabulous...However, take a look: there are so many great Coffee Stores at the plaza...Good time had by all. Love all  the wonderful choices. Bring Bags...bring a cart. Bring Money.'], ['Aguilera Taxes', 5, 'Beautiful day and we had drinks and shopped at the Ferry Building.'], ['Oakwood Welsh', 4, 'Good walkabout the Ferry Building and the surrounding pier area.

Restoration is fitting with good views to the vaulted ceiling.

But the real stars are thee foodie options. Good range of meat, veggie, gluten free snacks and desserts can be found.

Also some artisan shops selling food/drink items from around the world.

All in all a nice area of San Fran to chill out.']]

name: The Walt Disney Family Museum
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: Closed', 'Wednesday: Closed', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 5:30 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:30 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:30 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 5:30 PM']
reviews: [['Nicole Summers', 4, 'I have been wanting to go here for years and finally made it. The museum is in a beautiful area and we found (paid) parking quickly. The staff we encountered were friendly and helpful. I liked how the museum was set up chronologically as it helped build the history of the Disney family and how the brand developed. Depending on how much of a Disney fan you are will probably decide how long you spend. We spent about 1 1/2 hours while my brother and sister-in-law (who work/ed) for Disney spent over 3 hours.'], ['Dominic Wiker', 5, "Pleasantly surprised by this museum. Focus is very much on the man, his upbringing and professional development, his business, and the creative process. Along the way, there is plenty exposure to the characters and movies we're all familiar with. Exhibits are well organized and well presented. Not surprisingly, there's little on some of WD's less positive history esp related to labor, race and communism. That aside,  highly recommend."], ['Bo Beljaars', 5, 'This is a great place to visit if you’re a true Disney fan! Lots of history and some cool things to see. I loved the last part the most where they had a miniature version of Disneyland. Staff was very kind and also knew everything about Disney! It is a lot of reading throughout the museum. Personally I would have loved to have some more visuals or interactive things to do. Purchasing tickets at the desk is not possible, they must be bought upfront which is only possible with a credit card. Something to keep in mind!'], ['Erin Ray', 5, "Why hadn't we visited here yet?! It's been in the Presidio for 10yrs!\nIt was well worth it. If you're into Disneyland and how it came to be and how Disney started this whole thing, you won't be disappointed.\nLots of rare and one of a kind items. Like walking into a time capsule!"], ['David Montenegro', 5, 'Is beautiful!! I advise around 2:30-3:00 hrs for visiting this place if you like Disney. But if you live it and want to spend your time checking deeply into it, it might take around 5 hours. Lovely.']]

description:
The Walt Disney Family Museum is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization that was formally owned, operated and funded by the Walt Disney Family Foundation, a non-profit organization established by Disney's heirs including Diane Disney Miller, Disney's daughter and founder of the museum.  It is not formally associated with The Walt Disney Company, the media and entertainment enterprise.
The 40,000 square foot space in the main museum building features the newest technology and historic materials and artifacts to bring Disney’s achievements to life, with interactive galleries that include early drawings and animation, movies, music, listening stations, and a 12-foot diameter model of Disneyland.

name: Alcatraz Island
opening_hours: Opening hours unkown
reviews:
[['Chris Hughes', 5, 'The history at Alcatraz is amazing. The audio tour is a must do. The Park Rangers are very nice and very knowledgeable about everything on the island. Very nice gift shop that was clean and included a very friendly staff. The views of the city and the bay made great pictures. The weather in San Francisco in the summer time is the best. Great place to take the kids and send an afternoon.'], ['Jojo Irish', 4, "It was interesting. Honestly the best part was finding out about the native occupation of the island. Unfortunately by the time we finished the cell house they had closed the exhibit specifically dedicated to that part but the ranger lady told us all about it. She was a sweetheart. I wish the audio tour was more encompassing. I liked being guided through the area, but it only covered the cell house. I'm glad I went and would go back to see the Red Power exhibit."], ['Mapple Moore', 5, "(I posted this on ALCATRAZ TOURS as well because you guys were the same experience and it was all good!!))

Went here for a valentines date (odd choice I know, but we love our history) . Everything about this was such an experience.  I appreciate the focus was not just on the prison history but also focused on the indigenous rights movements that took place there. I didn't even know about it before!! I loved that they didn't shy away from telling the harsh truths about how POC were treated in the prison. And of those who were wrongfully sent there. Very eye opening, I'm sure there's lots more we don't know about.
Also the park (rangers?) Were talkative and helpful, and made sure we knew about the gardens which, as a gardener and plant lover, were my favorite.
I collect flowers and sand but when I heard we couldn't collect anything on the island settled for pictures, then I found out you can buy pieces of the foundation to take home and the funds keep the park going. I was happy to pay.
I'll have to come back because half the island was closed for nesting grounds (which I am pleased to hear is something they do to promote the wildlife in the area!) All around great place, wonderful experience,  but probably not a great place for a date if you're not both nerds.:)))"], ['john visneski', 5, 'A great tour. If you want to go, book early! Tickets go on sale 90 days in advance and they do sell out fairly quickly. We were able to get tickets for our visit by frequently checking the web site as cancelled tickets are put back on sale. I recommend going on the early bird (first tour of the day) at 0830. You can explore without overly large crowds that build as the day goes on. Tour is self guided with audio headphones included in the tour price. Bring a sweatshirt or zip-up as the temps can be cool even in summer. Boat ride over is only 10-15 minutes. You can stay as long as you like and catch any departing boat back when you are ready. There is a gift shop at the end of the tour for all your souvenir needs.'], ['Michael Wilson', 5, 'We had purchased our tickets in advance online. I highly recommend buying in advance as they do sellout. The weather has a tendency to be cloudy, windy with temperatures ( June 30th) in the mid sixties but felt cooler due to wind and mist coming off the bay. A light jacket is definitely a necessity.
There is  a significant amount of walking on the island. There is a rather long and steep concrete walkway leading to the actual prison. This could be a problem for people with mobility issues.
There is a tram that will take mobility impaired to the top of grounds but space is limited so plan  accordingly.
There are park Ranger guided tours and there are also self guided audio tours. It is strictly your choice. You can spend as much time as you like.  The ferry boats come about every half hour. I feel if you enjoy history and enjoy these type of things it is worth your time and money.']]

description:
Alcatraz Island (/ˈælkəˌtræz/) is a small island in San Francisco Bay, 1.25 miles (2.01 km) offshore from San Francisco, California, United States.[1] The island was developed in the mid-19th century with facilities for a lighthouse, a military fortification, and a military prison. In 1934, the island was converted into a federal prison, Alcatraz Federal Penitentiary. The strong currents around the island and cold water temperatures made escape nearly impossible, and the prison became one of the most notorious in American history.[4] The prison closed in 1963, and the island is now a major tourist attraction.
Beginning in November 1969, the island was occupied for more than 19 months by a group of Native Americans, initially primarily from San Francisco, who were later joined by AIM and other urban Indians from other parts of the country, who were part of a wave of Native American activists organizing public protests across the US through the 1970s. In 1972, Alcatraz was transferred to the Department of Interior to become part of Golden Gate National Recreation Area. It was designated as a National Historic Landmark in 1986.

name: Japanese Tea Garden
address: 75 Hagiwara Tea Garden Dr, San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Tuesday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Wednesday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Thursday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Friday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Saturday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM', 'Sunday: 9:00 AM – 5:45 PM']
reviews:
[['JD Hanson', 5, "This is one of the most beautiful and serene places I've ever been on Earth!
The admission is reasonable, my teenagers appreciated the beauty even if I had to slow them down a bit so we could soak it in and get good pictures. It makes for amazing photos!
The staff are friendly and keep the place spotless and perfect.
Best of all, it's in Golden Gate Park which is a bucket-list spot in one of the best cities on Earth.
I just wish it were bigger because I could have spent longer in the mood the scenery induced."], ['Ray Torres', 5, 'A must see if you are visiting San Francisco! Completely tailored grounds that gives the feeling of walking in Japan! Completely authentic, with a koi pond, pagoda, bridges, rock garden, statues of Buddha. Here is also a gift shop that sells Japanese items, like tea pots, elegant chop sticks, Buddha statues and other neat items. One of the best parts is the quaint outdoors tea house that overlooks a pond and gardens. The gardens is a great visit for families, couples and friends to relax and enjoy the gardens, especially if you love plants and appreciate nature! Price of $10 is reasonable for about one hour (or more) of serenity!'], ['Michael Allen Hansen (HardMinus)', 4, 'I love gardens, and consider good landscaping as expressive as any painting or poem out there. The tea garden is truly beautiful and I HIGHLY recommend using Big Bus as the means of transportation to get there. The breathtaking architecture that San Francisco has to offer, "primes" one and puts you in an observing state of mind.
Unfortunately, I realized that I have no taste for either tea or the different treats they offer. Besides, if an establishment sells refreshments, food/treats and has a "gift"shop, is there really a need to charge an entrance fee? That being said, the store was amazing!'], ['Gloria Guerra', 5, 'Have been going to The Japanese Tea garden since I was a child in the 1960s and am happy to see the park although changed remains largely unchanged.  The plants are manicured to perfection. The wooden bridge shaped like a parabola is immaculately preserved. A plaque I had not noticed stated the bridge's maker is a master and credited the builder. No longer are coins tossed in the water. As a child, I may have tried taking the coins. The giant Buddha statue near the bridge is not there, if it is I did not see it. The winding pathways over and through streams and ponds by way of wooden plank bridges and large granite blocks are preserved. Did not see too many fish. The park is an inspiration, and in my opinion, a must see. Because throughout my travels never have I seen a garden as intriguing and inspirational as The Golden Gate Park's "Japanese Tea Garden". The entry fee is $7, on a Sunday afternoon for a non-resident. No military discounts are given. The shop no longer sells as many various items like rice candy with edible wrapping and colorful paper kites as it once did. There are many tea sets though. Especially endearing are the many pine trees manicured into small short shapes. The Japanese Tea Garden is a treasure.'], ['Alberto Correa', 5, 'Japanese Tea Garden is a little piece of Japan in San Francisco Golden Gate Park. It is a romantic place to take your love one to enjoy some tea. People from all over the world come to San Francisco to enjoy this lovely place. I never regret to spend my time there. It is close to Museum and California Academy of Science. You are going to have a good time in the Japanese Tea Garden and around this area.']]

Climb to the highest part and you can get a great view of the city. Love!!!'], ['Kelly McClure', 5, "Dolores Park is a classic park to get the true SF experience. It overlooks the city in this almost surreal pool feeling park atmosphere that feels as though it distorts reality. Sit and enjoy yourself. Bring a beer or a joint or come sober. Just do you- it's the SF way. Check out the mission while you are here and definitely stay in the park to end your day with a bomb sunset."], ['Tony W', 5, "Mission Dolores is a park located in the Castro area of San Francisco. It's a place where people go with their dogs, their friends or alone to relax on the grass with a blanket, a good book or drink. You can take a blanket, a tent or a towel and lay out on the grass while taking in the surrounding views or socialize with other guests. From this park you are able to get at least a 180° view of downtown, the bay as well as other well known parts of the city.

The park is dog friendly and family friendly with people coming from all over the Bay Area and other places to soak up the sun and enjoy the vibe. The park has public restrooms as well as drinking fountains. You'll often find vendors here selling a number of food and non food items. The park itself is about 3 blocks away from Castro Street itself with a number of small eateries, bars and stores dotting the area. I've come to this park off and on for many years and have enjoyed myself each time. While the city is known to be on the cool side for the most part this park always seems much warmer and it could be due to the amount of direct sunlight the park gets in relation to other areas.

Overall it's a park that's worth visiting for the views alone and you may decide to stay awhile longer."], ['Cynthia Bazlamit', 5, 'Great place to picnic or hang out with friends, especially on a sunny day. Huge kids play area, and ice cream vendors make it fun for kids. Also, great views of San Francisco and close to many great shops and restaurants. Note on sunny days you may get a “contact high” from the high weed usage, but it’s all part of Dolores park charm!'], ['Julia Bennet', 5, 'View here is absolutely worth the visit. But the real draw is the people if you are visiting during the weekend, especially. Fantastic place to enjoy a relaxing day, people watching, playing games etc. You can find sun or shade and have a great experience either way. Parking can be tough. Sunset is a gorgeous time.']]

description:
Dolores Park is bounded by 18th Street on the north, 20th Street on the south, Dolores Street on the east and Church Street on the west. The northern end of Dolores Park is located directly across the street from Mission High School. On its eastern, southern and western sides, the park is surrounded by residential buildings of two to four stories, in various architectural styles.[3] South of the park is a hillside area known as "Dolores Heights," while The Castro neighborhood is located a short distance to the west. The park's topography is characterized by a strong slope from the southwest down to the northeast, offering an unobstructed northeast-looking view of downtown San Francisco, in particular from the southwest corner.[3]
Dolores Park offers several features including many tennis courts, a basketball court, a multi-purpose court, a soccer field, a pissoir, a children's playground, and a dog play area.[4] The southern half of the park is also notable for its views of the Mission district, downtown, the San Francisco Bay and the East Bay. The Muni Metro J-Church streetcar line runs through the park along its western border.

Unfortunately you cannot go inside so there is no point in actually going to the building.  Best to look at it from afar.'], ['Arky Barky', 5, 'I just checked it out from the street and it was super awesome. Why is it a pyramid? No idea. Is it super cool? If you're trying to catch the Cable Car on Clay & Powell, just look back down Clay and you catch a great pic of the Pyramid."], ['ヤヒルバロン', 5, 'Fun fact this landmark has survived numerous earthquakes :)']]

description:
The Transamerica building was commissioned by Transamerica CEO John (Jack) R. Beckett, with the claim that he wished to allow light in the street below. Built on the site of the historic Montgomery Block, it has a structural height of 853 feet (260 m) and has 48 floors of retail and office space.
Construction began in 1969 and finished in 1972, and was overseen by San Francisco–based contractor Dinwiddie Construction, now Hathaway Dinwiddie Construction Company. Transamerica moved its headquarters to the new building from across the street, where it had been based in a flatiron-shaped building now occupied by the Church of Scientology of San Francisco.[9]

name: Crissy Field
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['Eddie Valadez', 5, 'Crissy Field is one of the top areas of San Francisco to visit. Anytime i am in the Marina District neighborhood, i stop by Crissy Field to enjoy the great weather. I particularly like to walk in the area of Fort Point. The opportunity for people watching is also a good choice. The Crissy Field area has many opportunities for exercise, picnicking, and photos. The only challenge i encountered was parking. I definitely recommend a visit.'], ['Debbie C', 4, "I was there in Aug 2021 and it's partially under construction. I used Google maps to get around and had no problems.  Lots of people out enjoying the huge lawn, walking and biking trails. The buildings are interesting though very little is open. Awesome place."], ['David Rieker', 5, "Great place to go for a walk or a jog. Try swimming or just walk along the beach. It's also dog friendly. The weekend can get crowded, so come early. All in all, a beautiful way to start any day."], ['Ankita Podder', 5, 'Very nice open area for sitting for long hours and spending tine with friends and family . Has a pretty good view of thd golden gate bridge as well as nearing beach and sea .'], ['Meghneel Gore', 5, 'Want a great picnic place with a fantastic view of the Golden Gate Bridge? description:
Crissy Field is a public recreation area on the northern shore of the San Francisco Peninsula in California, United States, located just east of the Golden Gate Bridge. It includes restored tidal marsh and beaches.[1]
Crissy Field is a former United States Army airfield which is now part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area. Historically part of the Presidio of San Francisco, Crissy Field closed as an airfield after 1974. Under Army control, the site was affected by dumping of hazardous materials.[2] The National Park Service took control of the area in 1994 and, together with the Golden Gate National Parks Conservancy,[3] worked to restore the site until 2001, when the Crissy Field Center was opened to the public.[4] While most buildings have been preserved as they were in the 1920s, some have been transformed into offices, retail space, and residences.

reviews: [['Candy Menzies', 5, 'I went this museum to see a specific exhibit and was pleasantly surprised by the gorgeous location and views of the city and Golden Gate Bridge. The drive through the Presido and the winding hills with the bay below are beautiful. The museum itself is a perfect size for a half day trip. I loved 5hat I was able to enjoy the museum without it taking up my entire day. They have a cafe and lovely bookstore downstairs. The staff were kind and helpful and all in all it’s a great place to visit and I will be returning.'], ['Simone St Clare', 5, 'Small Museum set in a absolutely breathtaking location overlooking the entrance to San Francisco Bay. Beautifully curated exhibits, especially the Rodin sculptures. I was surprised to learn that the collection here at the Legion of Honor is one of the largest in the world other than the Rodin Museum in France. This is a place where you could spend a whole day by yourself and feel uplifted by the art and never bored. By the way, the cafe food is actually pretty good!'], ['Rosalie Arntzen', 5, 'The Legion is one of the best museums in San Francisco.  The Pompeii show is really great.  Very informative. Beautifully presented and shares a lot of really interesting information.  Parking can be a challenge.  Cafe is pricey but food is yummy.  Recommend the Legion 100%.'], ['burnt chicken', 5, "Great museum with an outstanding collection. Priced pretty reasonably for general admission ($15) and is sure to please just about anyone with it's wide variety of pieces from paintings to furniture to even whole rooms reassembled. Would highly recommend."], ['Joe B', 5, 'Art museum with a focus on classical art with some interesting exhibits. Absolutely stunning and beautiful location, worth spending some time in the surrounding area to get some great pictures. Public transport is kind of a problem, it drops you off near, but you have to hike up. Definitely worth a visit and you can visit the DeYoung museum the same day for free!']]

description:
The National Order of the Legion of Honour (French: Ordre national de la Légion d'honneur), formerly the Royal Order of the Legion of Honour (Ordre royal de la Légion d'honneur), is the highest French order of merit, both military and civil. Established in 1802 by Napoleon Bonaparte, it has been retained (and slightly altered) by all later French governments and régimes.
The order's motto is Honneur et Patrie ("Honour and Fatherland"), and its seat is the Palais de la Légion d'Honneur next to the Musée d'Orsay, on the left bank of the Seine in Paris.[a]

name: San Francisco Museum of Modern Art
opening_hours: ['Monday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Wednesday: Closed', 'Thursday: 1:00 – 8:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Amir Hashemi', 5, "I was lucky enough to visit the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art on my recent trip to the city. I have to say, I was absolutely blown away by the architecture and design of the museum. It's really modern and has a great influence of Scandinavian design style. There's so much space and light, and the geometry is just perfect. The museum is also very well laid out and easy to navigate. Elevators are available but the stairs are very nice and hardly crowded. As for the art on display, it's just phenomenal."], ['Jaideep Subedar', 5, 'Fantastic space, exhibits and people! Loved the experience.

This is a very large museum in the middle of the city and is definitely a must see for anyone who is interested in modern art. They also have some amazing Picasso, Rothko, and other brilliant works! I would plan on being here for 2-3 hours or more.

Pro tip: get yourself signed up for some of the exhibits that have a queue to get in right when you get in so you can do a floor or two before you get a message to visit the limited/controlled spaces.'], ['Ray Torres', 5, 'A must see museum in the city! Has 7 levels of art that is full of a diverse use of art mediums! Huge sculptures, surrealists and abstracts. One exhibit had lights like a disco and a drum set for anyone to play! We were fortunate to see the special exhibit by Diego Rivera. This is a unique museum. You will not be disappointed if you love all forms of art!'], ['Bruce DeWald', 5, 'Spent a little over 2 hours here and got to walk through probably about 90% of the exhibits. Would need to spend much longer if you’re really taking it all in, but I thought it was the perfect amount of time and leaves you wanting a little more to come back again. Enjoyed the wide variety of art and the museum building itself is beautiful.'], ['Zephyr Neumann', 4, "The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art is a place that is worth visiting, should you enjoy art, architecture, and a quiet time wandering many, many galleries. It is a very neat Museum to explore, although it likely is not to everyone's taste.

Entry was relatively affordable, especially for the size of the museum. With at least 4 floors to explore, there is ample to see, and we spent a good few hours checking out the art and exhibits until the time we were getting burned out, and there was still even more to see."]]

description:
The San Francisco Museum of Modern Art (SFMOMA) is a modern and contemporary art museum located in San Francisco, California. A nonprofit organization, SFMOMA holds an internationally recognized collection of modern and contemporary art, and was the first museum on the West Coast devoted solely to 20th-century art. The museum's current collection includes over 33,000 works of painting, sculpture, photography, architecture, design, and media arts, and moving into the 21st century.[1] The collection is displayed in 170,000 square feet (16,000 m2) of exhibition space, making the museum one of the largest in the United States overall, and one of the largest in the world for modern and contemporary art.[2]
Founded in 1935 in the War Memorial Building, the museum opened in its Mario Botta designed home in the SoMa district in 1995. SFMOMA reopened on May 14, 2016, following a major three-year-long expansion project by Snøhetta architects.[3] The expansion more than doubles the museum's gallery spaces and provides almost six times as much public space as the previous building, allowing SFMOMA to showcase an expanded collection along with the Doris and Donald Fisher Collection of contemporary art.[4]

name: The Painted Ladies
address: Steiner St &, Hayes St, San Francisco
opening_hours: Opening hours unkown
reviews:
[['Carmen L', 4, "Not as busy on a weekday so easier to get a shot however it was quite hilly and steep to walk to coming from our hotel located in the downtown core. The painted ladies are iconic and was what I expected, although I do have to say some other houses leading up to the ladies are much more interesting to look at and just as impressive (also much more brightly painted). Nonetheless if you're a fan of Full House it's a sight to see. The park adjacent to the houses is nice to hang out at with lots of people just sitting on the hill with their dogs."], ['David Vazquez', 4, "Pretty to look at and photograph. Alamo Square is the park across the street and you can spend some time there if you'd like. You'll notice that there is a honey bear in the windows of one of two of them and also around other homes in San Francisco. This is a local artist that has begun sort of a savage hunt of the bears but participants must disclose their address to participate. I wouldn't want my address being public but hey, to each is own."], ['Shivam Shah', 5, 'Beautiful place...
Beautiful houses...
Good drive...
The park in front is good for taking photos of Painted Ladies..
Parking is tough to find... But if you wait for sometime... You might get lucky...
Must visit for San Francisco'], ['Nick Ennis', 3, "Some nice houses. Not sure what all the fuss is about to be honest. We saw much nicer ones in San Francisco
Used in the Full House series my wife told me after but I didn't watch it, so sadly meaningless to me.
It's just a photo op as far as I'm aware. You can't go in them. It's a steep hill to get there as you'd expect, so if you're walking it, don't."], ['The Bobs', 2, 'Disappointing, park is nice.  There are more attractive homes.']]

description: In American architecture, painted ladies are Victorian and Edwardian houses and buildings repainted, starting in the 1960s, in three or more colors that embellish or enhance their architectural details.https://www.google.com/search?q=The+Painted+Ladies&as_epq=&as_oq=&as_eq=&as_nlo=&as_nhi=&lr=lang_en&cr=&as_qdr=all&as_sitesearch=&as_occt=any&safe=images&as_filetype=&tbs=

name: The Wave Organ
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews:
[['Jenny Pollock', 4, 'Art music and the ocean converge here. If you like any of the three it’s worth a visit.

The waves push air into the organ making music. It’s a unique San Francisco experience.

Enjoy the view of the Golden Gate Bridge and the boats in the bay.

This is right by a yacht club so there are boats in the marina.

It’s a little bit of walk on flat ground to get to the wave organ.'], ['Goesto Restaurants', 5, "This is a cool place to visit. We barely heard anything because we were there at the wrong time but it is a cool place. Nice view of the city and the ocean, peaceful, there's a little cove-like sitting area to shield from the wind. Recommend."], ['anelise gray', 5, 'Go at high tide to hear it play with the ocean waves. One of a kind and unique Art/music. Love it!'], ['Mike Jones', 4, 'Nice short walk almighty the bay. Best to visit at higher tide. Neat seeing old cemetery pieces recycled for use in this. The covered bench had the best sound.'], ['Marc Albert', 4, 'It’s a lovely place to hang out and see the sights in the bay. There’s a great view of Alcatraz and the two bridges. When we were there, during low tide, the organ was completely mute. The signs say it’s best during high tide.']]

address: 50 Hagiwara Tea Garden Dr, San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM', 'Wednesday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM', 'Thursday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM', 'Friday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM', 'Saturday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM', 'Sunday: 9:30 AM – 5:15 PM']
reviews:
[['Ben Miles', 5, "There is no need to question the global status of this establishment in the art world. It's on par with all of the great world class art museums, the collection is magnificent. What makes it more special is the special exhibitions. Countless shows showcasing not only well known artists but also some lesser known. Those lesser known might just be the best part. In my opinion, any time you have the opportunity to learn something new it's a great day!"], ['Lisa Immel', 5, "Wonderful art exhibit! Could spend the whole day looking at everything!
My only request?
Cool it down a bit more. Unless it's necessary to have it at a certain temp. All those people create body heat and it got a little toasty.
Otherwise a wonderful experience! Looking forward to our next trip!"], ['Jim Pacelli', 5, 'What a lovely place. Two special shows going now now. Just re-opened. Everybody was friendly & very helpful. A very pleasant afternoon. It is worth a trip. Always something of interest to explore, the Cafe food offering were very good. Well done an presented with care...'], ['Joyce Asmus', 5, "Thus museum has a great collection of American artists' paintings and sculptures.   There are historical motifs through modern art, and collections from the Pacific Islands, Africa, and a good representation of Indigenous American pieces.  In addition, we were lucky to see the traveling exhibit of the official Obama portraits.  These were exceptional and well worth seeing.   The museum cafe has a great selection of well-prepared food to eat, and is reasonably priced."], ['Mio Villagomez', 5, "What a wonderful pairing. Calder more than held his own with Picasso.
The exhibition places Calder's works for maximum effect and are an artistic triumph in their own right.
I had no idea on the about the proximity of these two wonderful artists."]]

description:
The museum opened in 1895 as an outgrowth of the California Midwinter International Exposition of 1894 (a fair modeled on the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition of the previous year). It was housed in an Egyptian revival structure which had been the Fine Arts Building at the fair. The building was badly damaged in the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, and was closed for a year and a half for repairs. Before long, the museum's steady development called for a new space to better serve its growing audiences. Michael de Young responded by planning the building that would serve as the core of the de Young facility through the 20th century. Louis Christian Mullgardt, the coordinator for architecture for the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition, designed the Spanish-Plateresque-style building. The new structure was completed in 1919 and formally transferred by de Young to the city's park commissioners. In 1921, de Young added a central section, together with a tower that would become the museum's signature feature, and the museum began to assume the basic configuration that it retained until 2000. De Young's efforts were honored with the changing of the museum's name to the M. H. de Young Memorial Museum. Another addition, a west wing, was completed in 1925, the year de Young died. In 1929 the original Egyptian-style building was declared unsafe and demolished.
By 1949, the elaborate cast concrete ornamentation of the original de Young was determined to be a hazard and removed because the salt air from the Pacific had rusted the supporting steel.

address: Pier 15 Embarcadero at, Green St, San Francisco

reviews:
[['Ginger Cheng', 5, "The best surprise we get for our trip! The museum is good for all ages. My 9 & 11-year-old boys got so  much fun there that we visited it three days in a row! There are over a hundred exhibits there and people working at the workshop are actively creating more exhibits with ideas collected from all over the world! This is world class creation and innovation! Even the clock there is made with excellent thoughts and fun to watch! Don't miss it! It is way better than the expensive just-for-show California Academy of Sciences"], ['KARTIK YADAV', 5, 'Fun even without kids, lots of tactile exhibits which are interactive and quite engaging.  I figured I would be in here perhaps an hour or two, but I was here about 4+ hours playing with everything as it was so much fun trying everything out.  At first I thought it was pretty pricey, but there is so much to do, I can understand the price.
Fun even without kids, lots of tactile exhibits which are interactive and quite engaging.  I figured I would be in here perhaps an hour or two, but I was here about 4+ hours playing with everything as it was so much fun trying everything out.  At first I thought it was pretty pricey, but there is so much to do, I can understand the price.'], ['Adam Bjorndahl', 5, "Wow, I expected this place to be fun, but it was even better than I imagined! There are countless exhibits showcasing some interesting phenomenon or other, all very thoughtfully designed to be both fun and educational. I can't believe the sheer variety and quantity of high-quality exhibits! All told, probably one of the best exhibits I've ever seen, honestly. You can easily spend 3–4 hours here and not see everything."], ['Jake L', 5, "This place is way, way bigger than you expected.

Easily the best science museum I've visited, with probably 200+ fully interactive and explained exhibits. Each of them provides a very immediate and obvious effect, along with enough information for adults or older kids to understand WHY the effect happened.

We spent 3 hours here, but could have spent 4-5 if we were had time. Definitely worth a visit as an adult, don't be fooled into thinking it's a kid-focused museum just because everything is interactive!"], ['David Della Lana', 5, 'Kids will have unending fun; Engaging for adults, too. Start early, plan to visit for hours, expect to spend the entire day - almost impossible to leave! description:
The Exploratorium was founded by physicist and educator Frank Oppenheimer and opened in 1969 at the Palace of Fine Arts, its home until January 2, 2013. On April 17, 2013, the Exploratorium reopened at Piers 15 and 17 on San Francisco's Embarcadero. The historic interior and exterior of Pier 15 were renovated extensively prior to the move, and are divided into several galleries mainly separated by content, including the physics of seeing and listening (Light and Sound), Human Behavior, Living Systems, Tinkering (including electricity and magnetism), the Outdoor Gallery, and the Bay Observatory Gallery, which focuses on the local environment, weather, and landscape.
Since the museum's founding, over 1,000 participatory exhibits have been created, approximately 600 of which are on display at any given time. The exhibit-building workshop space is contained within the museum and is open to view. In addition to the public exhibition space, the Exploratorium has been engaged in the professional development of teachers, science education reform, and the promotion of museums as informal education centers since its founding. Since Oppenheimer's death in 1985, the Exploratorium has expanded into other domains, including its 50,000-page website and two iPad apps on sound and color. It has also inspired an international network of participatory museums working to engage the public with general science education.[5] The new Exploratorium building is also working to showcase environmental sustainability efforts as part of its goal to become the largest net-zero museum in the country.[6]

reviews: [['Kathy Hatten', 5, 'We took a group of customers to enjoy Triples Alley to enjoy  the food, drinks and watch the players warm up on the field. They had a blast and later we took our seats and found out we were sitting in “The Lucky Row” and we all won round trip airfare tickets with Alaskan Airlines. Such a fun surprise. Plus we all loved getting the a Hawaiian shirt giveaways. The best part was the exciting win over the Brewers. Thanks Alaskan   Airlines for the nice donation. Can’t wait to fly and try it out.'], ['Sylvain Saurel', 5, "I took advantage of my visit to San Francisco to experience the atmosphere of a baseball game in America. The Giants' arena is truly beautiful, and we had a great time as a family. I was amazed to see all the snack bars and other restaurants inside Oracle Park. The same goes for the official Giants store, which is located right inside the stadium.\nSomething that we do not find in France in soccer stadiums for example. There is something to be inspired in terms of marketing in any case.\nA good time. I wouldn't hesitate to go back to see a game if I go back to San Francisco one day."], ['Serena Christy', 5, 'Oracle Park! Wow what a great experience! Love those Giants! All the staff are caring, friendly and wonderful people. Thank you Bob, you were more than just an Usher, you made us smile and laugh and you are very knowledgeable on your Giants history! Great Experience!'], ['stacey kenney', 5, 'Best baseball park hands down. Food is so delicious,  had a burger and garlic fries. Wonderful. Neat to see the ocean next to the park and nice breeze.  True fans there too. Parking can be tough, some lots wanted $100 to park. Late to game looking 4 parking. Go early'], ['Joseph Thomas', 4, 'Excellent location.  Beautiful views!  Would be so much better if it was a football stadium though.  Can you imagine a fun sport like football being played in such a prime location?  Not slow like baseball.  All action!  Perhaps one day they will convert it to a football field or a cool food truck park.  So many options.']]

reviews:
[['Lauren Jones', 5, 'Really nice zoo. Staff are nice. Maps dotted all around the zoo to help plan your route. There’s a little steam train for 7$ once inside that goes round twice. The indoor insect part is really underrated. Highly recommend.'], ['zachary Valentine', 5, 'What an amazing zoo! Lots of interaction! Amazing well kept animals!
The staff here are amazing and answer any questions you may have.
We rode the train and it was fun!

Animals very well taken care of

10 outta 10 will visit again when the next exhibits are open!'], ['Shane', 5, 'great place for little ones to run around, lots of grassy areas for a little picnic. When the pandemic is over the rides will open back up and the HUGE jungle gym playground. Tons of different animals including all the normal zoo animals but also has some exotics, like a couple of really cool snow leopards. great little cafe you can get lunch and adult beverages. also right next to the beach so if you want to plan a really cool day its that easy. San Francisco Zoo is a great place.'], ['Brandon Aviles', 5, 'Let's be clear about this establishment - it may not be the over-the-top best zoo you'll ever go to in your life. Oakland and San Diego would probably compete there. However, I am rating this a 5 because it satisfies all your "Enjoyable Zoo Trip" requirements. Animals? Check. Comfortable walking amounts? Check. Snack and gift shop? Check. Alcohol? Check. Pretty atmosphere with plenty of effort put into both infrastructure and animal care. The only thing I question is the allocated space for the little monkeys (I think capuchin?) The big monkeys are clearly cared for and not suffering at all but the little ones have like 50% of the park all to themselves. If the big monkeys take over someday, I'd like to think they understood it wasn't personal. All in all, great place to visit, though I couldn't recommend living there.'], ['me C', 5, 'It was a nice outage, clean.  We arrived at 12 on Saturday.  Our entry time was 1230-1pm.  Parking was full so we paid the 25 for Valet. It was a little confusing to see a Valet sign near the ticket line and to be told to drive to the to the exit for Valet.  There should be signs consistent with the verbal instruction.  Valet was polite and professional. The line to pay for tickets and parking moved fast.  The park was clean and not super crowded.']]
