description:
The zoo's main entrance (one located on the north side across Sloat Boulevard and one block south of the Muni Metro L Taraval line) is to the west, on the ocean side.
Originally named the Fleishhacker Zoo[6] after its founder, banker and San Francisco Parks Commission president Herbert Fleishhacker, planning for construction began in 1929 on the site adjacent to what was once the largest swimming pool in the United States, the Fleishhacker Pool.[1]  The area was also already home to a children’s playground, an original (circa 1921) Michael Dentzel/Marcus Illions carousel, and the Mother’s Building, a haven for women and their children. Most of the exhibits were populated with animals transferred from Golden Gate Park, including two zebras, a cape buffalo, five rhesus monkeys, two spider monkeys, and three elephants (Virginia, Marjorie, and Babe).

name: San Francisco Cable Car Museum
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Graham Pierce', 5, "This is an amazing working museum!  (I say working, because this is where they actually power the cables that run the cars.) If you are a fan of transportation technology, or just retro technology in general, this place is a must-visit!
The way the cable cars work is totally unique--they're more like a rope tow lift that you see on small hills at skiing places--then they are like any other kind of transportation.
This museum shows you the various parts of the cable cars, with detailed explanations of how they work, and it lets you observe the motors for the cables, as well as how the cables go out under the streets.
The video they have on loop is adorable too!"], ['K Owen - Abesamis', 4, "Ride a cable car to the museum! It's a great place to learn about the cable cars and their history in the city... can be packed in the summer. Although the visit in the museum should only take a half hour or so. Bring your out of town friends, very educational and it is easy to find from the waterfront and piers... it was neat."], ['Renni Christensen', 5, 'A must for anyone who is a fan of history or just wanting to get the full SF experience. It was neat taking the cable car,  thinking of all the different  people over the decades that had been sitting there just as you were. The museum was free, and you can stroll around for as little or long as you like. The history of the original invention, the engineering and the gentleman below still working on the machinery yo this day - 👌. Only downfall is when we wanted to grab a car back to the wharf, they were all full. So husband says "it's  only a few blocks." I don't care if you think it's a good idea to get your steps in, work the cannoli off from lunch, or just "see the sights" on foot.  Don't do it. An hour and a half later we got back to the car with $24 in unused one-way tickets for the cable car. Everyone was silent, sweaty, hungry and ANGRY. It was a poor way to end a fun experience. But otherwise, highly recommend!... Just not with my family.'], ['KARTIK YADAV', 5, "This was my personal favorite part of our visit to San Francisco. Perhaps not the largest or most flashy museum, but maintained by passionate volunteers and showcasing an incredibly important and iconic part of San Francisco's history and present. Being surrounded by the operating machinery of the cable cars definitely adds to the awe and ambiance"], ['Tara Badrinath', 5, 'What an amazing place! The mechanical engineering marvel operating the cable cars, designed a hundred years ago was a pleasure to watch. The museum by itself had so much of interesting information, it should be a must see for the younger generation, to learn about the creativity and ingenuity of their ancestors.']]

name: USS Pampanito
opening_hours: ['Monday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 6:00 PM']
reviews: [['Justin Bradley', 4, 'Price is mostly fair for what you get. Audio tour was great while i had service. Was only able to get 3 in before signal was lost. However, it is absolutely worth the fee to experience. Only open on certain days. Ship is open on opposite days. No wait to enter.'], ['Matt Granderson', 5, "Very well kept example of a WWII submarine.  Instrumentation panels and equipment is nice, sections of diesels and torpedoes have a plexiglass cutout allowing you to see real cross sectional internals. Worth seeing if you're in the area.  As a submarine veteran I'm partial to these things--also all submarine vets ask for the log book and sign in."], ['Diane Barker', 5, "Absolutely loved it! I'm super short so getting to hop through me sized hatches was pretty great. Can't imagine more than a couple of folks on board at once though, so hats off to the original brave crew!"], ['Rob Kimmel', 5, "Ok I couldn't get anyone to go with me inside, but a really cool sub (bigger and better than the Soviet sub at Long Beach). And lots of explanatory displays outside in case you don't want to pay to board. Pricing is good too, adults $25 but seniors only $15. Propellers and torpedoes outside."], ['The Bandit', 5, 'It was a great place full of rich history but is not for the faint if heart as it is hard to maneuver and I would say is only for true historical lovers. But it was super cool and compared to other places is the area is pretty cheap. Overall a 10/10 place to visit!']]

description:
USS Pampanito (SS-383/AGSS-383), a  Balao-class submarine, was a United States Navy ship, the third one named for the pompano fish. She completed six war patrols from 1944 to 1945 and served as a United States Naval Reserve training ship from 1960 to 1971. She is now a National Historic Landmark, preserved as a memorial and museum ship in the San Francisco Maritime National Park Association located at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco, California.
Pampanito's keel was laid down by the Portsmouth Navy Yard in Kittery, Maine, on 15 March 1943. She was launched on 12 July 1943, sponsored by Mrs. James Wolfender, and commissioned on 6 November 1943, with Lieutenant Commander Charles B. Jackson, Jr., in command.

reviews:
[['Daryoush Nekooi', 5, 'This is a community built project that depicts the theme and culture of San Francisco. This is a beautiful place that took 20 years to make. Each step has been carefully crafted by the people of San Francisco and that togetherness is something we felt on our visit. They are friendly and diverse, but they all come together.

In a more literal sense, the steps show the marine life throughout the seasons and it is beautiful.

The view from the top is amazing too!'], ['Joe Jung', 3, "If you can spare 30 minutes during your trip and are not too far from your hotel, it's a cool place to visit. Lock your rental car and do not leave anything valuable in the car!  It's a hike to the top. Wear walking shoes. A nice view of the city from the stairs. Tiles were installed by the neighborhood."], ['Rhiain Nathanson', 5, 'Lovely!
A definite must if you visit the area. Walk all the way to the top as the view is spectacular.
The staircase is a beautiful work of art and you really have to walk up to experience each sections beauty.'], ['Latha Srikanth', 5, 'How creative one can become is an example. The tiles have a beautiful design. Every landing gives a different view of the  city. Beautiful place for photo shoot'], ['Gresford Thomas', 5, 'Lush and well manicured landscape as you ascend or descend the ornately tiled staircase. It was not too crowded on a Sunday afternoon. A great way to see the city and get those steps in!']]

name: Yerba Buena Gardens
opening_hours: ['Monday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Thursday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Friday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Saturday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM', 'Sunday: 6:00 AM – 10:00 PM']
reviews: [['Alisa Damaso', 5, "Yerba Buena Gardens is such a beautiful, spacious, and relaxing outdoor area. Their free events are amazing. I've come here a handful of times for SF Uke Jam over the years, and it's always been great, wholesome fun! I love when passersby stumble into events and enjoy the festivities."], ['Arnold Bhebhe', 5, 'Great place to check out. It has some great spots for an evening walk, and just relaxing. There is also bowling and ice skating - which is super cool!\n\nDefinitely recommend for you to check out this place!'], ['Meanne Santos', 5, 'I like the sound of the waterfalls and I can meditate in that area.'], ['T. Farris', 5, 'Seemingly in the middle of everything in the Financial District. This place is very photogenic. Different Museums across from here in every direction. Also, nice place to bring a lunch and sit out people watching. Nice watch fixture in the middle and a Target right there also.'], ['Paulette Norris', 4, "Had such a wonderful day here. Read the other reviews and was nervous it would be too busy and that we would have other people in our photos -- went on a Sunday and it wasn't too crowded at all. The staff and especially associate manager Will was so helpful and we definitely have the pictures to show for it. Really memorable part of our trip and would recommend it for those looking for a cool photo opportunity!"]]

description:
Yerba Buena was the name of the town in the Mexican territory of Alta California that became the city of San Francisco, California, after it was claimed by the United States in 1846. It was itself named after the yerba buena (Micromeria douglasii) plant which used to be abundant in the area.[2] The plant's common name, yerba buena, is an alternate form of the Spanish hierba buena (meaning "good herb").
The idea of building a conference center, under the name Yerba Buena Center, in downtown San Francisco was a further development of the idea stemming from the late 1950s to redevelop the city center, particularly the industrial areas that were gradually falling into disuse. At the heart of the proposal was the vision of the city transforming from an industrial to a tourist-conventioneering city.[citation needed] The idea of the Yerba Buena Center itself first emerged in the early 1960s.[3] At that time there was a concern about how development could occur in the downtown area. The South of Market area offered hundreds of acres of flat land at low land prices.  Various corporate committees were founded to lobby for the redevelopment, which would also include high-rise office buildings, a vast parking garage, and a sports center. At the center of operations was the San Francisco Redevelopment Agency (SFRA) first headed by Joseph Alioto, who would go on to become mayor of the city in 1968. The area of the development was regarded as a blighted area of the city, even referred to by local media, local business and city officials as 'skid row'.[citation needed] However, the developers did not figure on the persistence of the local community, the vast majority of which were aged, male, ex-industrial workers who lived alone in the many cheap hotels in the area. Together the latter formed the Tenants and Owners in Opposition to Redevelopment (TOOR). Their demand was to be rehoused in the area in low-rent housing. The case went to court where the judge, Stan Weigel, judged in favor of TOOR.[4] Things changed with the election of a new city mayor, George Moscone, in 1976, who spearheaded construction. The Gardens was later built as part of a deal by Mayor Moscone with developers to "set aside land and funds for cultural institutions such as museums, exhibits, and theaters."[5]

reviews: [['Michael Wilson', 4, 'We were doing some shopping in the area. There are not any real public restrooms. They have some larger semi permanent portable restrooms set up by the park. They were clean and appeared to be well maintained. We used them and were pleasantly surprised that they were actually clean.'], ['Kc The KiD', 5, 'Old structure.  Latin on the building'], ['Wizzley Raccoon', 5, 'Iconic park where a classic Dirty Harry scene was filmed- great spot to sit after you grab a Slice of Pizza from Slice House and a bottle of wine (discrete- wink-wink : no alcohol allowed in park!). Cool statue dedicated to Firemen of SF by Lilly Coit (Google read about her story- iconic SF Character along the lines of Emperor Norton!) And a view of the tower named after her that also serves to thank and remember SF Firemen!'], ['Larrolyn Ford', 5, "I was just roaming around the city looking for a USPS, came across this large and beautiful square. They were a lot of dogs in front of it, it's probably a dog park, but all of the dogs were having fun chilling without any gates so they were roaming around freely. There is a lot of open seats and it seems that on every corner of the square there are different buses that are going past. Definitely a beautiful space that I would highly recommend. Just walking through to relax"], ['Scott', 4, "Nice Urban Park in a great part of San francisco. There are definitely some creepy people here at times, but it's a beautiful Green space next to a big historic church. Tons of great Italian restaurants nearby."]]

reviews: [['Lexie Maloney', 5, 'Amazing. The energy here was so fun. An affordable place to spend some time, have a good time, and learn a little something. All the machines are well taken care of. I came here to try out the arm wrestling machine featured in the princess diaries.. I lost.'], ['Cee Rose', 5, "I love it! It’s completely free to walk around and look at everything. There is an ATM and a change machine. Bathrooms nearby. Hand sanitizer everywhere. This is a super fun place to spend the afternoon. I am so glad that this place exists for kids to get a glimpse of history they might care about. It was an honor to visit such a collection. Oh and the foot massage machines that they DON'T have at county fairs anymore! Did that one twice! :D Definitely check it out. There are some parking lots nearby if you drive around."], ['Jiun-Jie Yang', 5, 'Probably one of the coolest spots in fisherman’s wharf. It’s free to get in and you get to play with vintage arcade machines, and most are around 25-50 cents to play. Cheap entertainment with novelty and wow factor. Would recommend at least stopping by. Need to bring a bit of cash though.'], ['Maximilian Alleze', 5, 'Great place to be a kid again. Never seen so many historic arcade machines before. Certainly worth a visit when you are in the area. They also have modern arcades if you prefer that.'], ['Dipali Desai', 5, 'So much fun! Totally have a use for your change jar. It has a very ragtime/boardwalk empire atmosphere that is always entertaining but sometimes macabre and bizarre. Love the variety of fortune-telling machines!']]

description:
The museum's original owner, Ed Zelinsky, began collecting at age 11. His games were exhibited in the 1920s at Playland. In 1972 Playland closed and Musée Mécanique became a part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area.[2] The museum moved into the basement of Cliff House, just a few blocks north and across the Great Highway from the Playland site.[when?] Zelinsky's son, Dan Zelinsky, took a temporary job in the 1970s maintaining the collection.[3]
The museum was featured in the 2001 film The Princess Diaries[4] and in a 2011 episode of the Japanese television show GameCenter CX.[citation needed]

description:
Prior to the opening of the Golden Gate Bridge and the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge, it was the principal automobile ferry terminal connecting San Francisco with Marin County by way of Sausalito to the north, and the East Bay by way of Berkeley. It was designated part of U.S. Route 101 and U.S. Route 40. The ferries began operation by the Golden Gate Ferry Company. In early-1929, the Golden Gate Ferry Company merged with the competing auto ferry system of the Southern Pacific railroad, with ferry service to the Hyde Street Pier taken over by the new "Southern Pacific-Golden Gate Ferries, Ltd." starting on May 1, 1929.[2]
Today, the pier is part of the San Francisco Maritime National Historical Park. Various historical ships are anchored to the pier, some available for self-guided or docent-led tours. Among the ships on display or in storage are the Balclutha, an 1886 square rigged sailing ship, as well as C.A. Thayer, Eureka, Alma, Hercules, Eppleton Hall, and over one hundred smaller craft.

description:
The San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge, known locally as the Bay Bridge, is a complex of bridges spanning San Francisco Bay in California. As part of Interstate 80 and the direct road between San Francisco and Oakland, it carries about 260,000 vehicles a day on its two decks.[3][4] It has one of the longest spans in the United States.
The toll bridge was conceived as early as the California Gold Rush days, with "Emperor" Joshua Norton famously advocating for it, but construction did not begin until 1933. Designed by Charles H. Purcell,[6][7] and built by American Bridge Company, it opened on Thursday, November 12, 1936, six months before the Golden Gate Bridge. It originally carried automobile traffic on its upper deck, with trucks, cars, buses and commuter trains on the lower, but after the Key System abandoned rail service, the lower deck was converted to all-road traffic as well. In 1986, the bridge was unofficially dedicated to former California Governor James Rolph.[8]

Hand sanitizer and sinks available'], ['Frank d', 5, 'Lots of places to see and buy souvenirs'], ['Michael Wilson', 4, "There are a numerous amount of things to do at the Fisherman's Wharf. These things range from river cruises,souvenir shops and many excellent seafood restaurants.\nThere is a W.W. 2 submarine that you can actually go in if desired. The cruises should be purchased early as some of them will sell out daily. There is plenty of public parking for about $40 daily. There is no in and out of the parking area.  If you have to travel to different piers or other areas I would recommend buying a Muni ( electric cable car) day pass for $5. The weather has a tendency to be on the cooler side and can be windy due to close proximity to the water. I recommend bringing a light jacket. This is a good place for family vacations or just a day trip."]]

Biggest complaint, however, is Sandy Allen’s, the world’s tallest woman, memorabilia being hidden in a dark hallway between rooms (the lizard man has more attention and it’s just someone who got tattoos, big whoop). Please consider putting her memorabilia in a proper location.'], ['Anita Brighton', 5, "Our family loved it (8, 9, 44 and 46 year-olds).  There is lots to see in high quality interactive sets. It would be great if they had a Ripley's Museum part of the museum where it had historical artifacts/collectibles/memorabilia old merch and Ripley's related and a gift/souvenir shop!"], ['Adam Nelms', 5, 'It is Expensive, but if you combine with the wax museum next door they offer a combo ticket to bring the price down a bit. I'll update after my visit. Excited to see everything!"], ['Steven Brothers', 4, "The whole family has a surprisingly great time here. I was initially nervous about plunking down $30 per person (kids are the same price), but the kids really wanted to do it. name: Misión San Francisco de Asís
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: Closed', 'Wednesday: Closed', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM']
reviews: [['Marie', 5, 'This was such a lovely piece of history to explore. The original mission church and grounds were beautiful and peaceful to wander around. We were unable to check out the larger basilica as there was a wedding happening when we were there. This was well worth the $7 entrance fee.'], ['JIM SALINAS', 5, "246 years old.  The 1st building in San Francisco and the oldest building still standing. There's so much to see here there's so much to experience going through the graveyard and seeing the earliest inhabitants of the city is such an inspiring thing and there's also a wonderful little museum with a lot of religious artifact that heighten the experience here at the old mission. Our holy father was here not too many years ago. It is the birthplace of San Francisco. Its also here  before the birth of the United States of America. If you're visiting San Francisco it's a place you should not miss."], ['Leon Chang', 4, "The stand out here is their chapel with the stained glass depictions of the patron saints of all the various California missions. As far as the rest of the mission,  it's nice but nothing to otherwise distinguish it."], ['Viridiana Garcia', 5, 'Wow. Authentic catholic church. I felt as if I was in Mexico. The mission itself is amazing and the small tour area shows you the rich history of the church. Walking through the cemetery reminds you of how fragile life is. Within these walls, miracles are prayed for, and answered.'], ['Carl Flores', 5, 'First time visiting the mission and it was beautiful. The art and details in the sacred artwork was amazing. Plus the history of the place. A great learning experience and history as well.']]
description: Mission San Francisco de Asís, commonly known as Mission Dolores, is a Spanish Californian mission and the oldest surviving structure in San Francisco.https://www.google.com/search?q=Misión+San+Francisco+de+Asís&as_epq=&as_oq=&as_eq=&as_nlo=&as_nhi=&lr=lang_en&cr=&as_qdr=all&as_sitesearch=&as_occt=any&safe=images&as_filetype=&tbs=

name: Language of the Birds
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['Ted Gast', 4, 'A beautiful place to chill and relax'], ['Michael Wu PhD', 4, 'This modern art installation/sculpture makes the Jazz Mural behind it comes to live. It is one of the less know secrets of SF right on the border between Chinatown and North Beach (aka Little Italy).'], ['Ahmet Zambrotta', 5, 'Looks better at night great place for a photo shoot'], ['Tu Lam', 4, "I like it when the art is created around the neighborhood. And by this I mean that the used books in a sense that they are birds in flight. But I feel like it is also a nod to City Lights bookstore. The fact that this has been here for a long time but it also shows that it's been well-maintained and kept up."], ['Albertino M.', 4, "Language of the Birds is a public attraction available 24/7, but it's better to see it at night. Located on the corner of Broadway/Columbus Ave, it's basically string light with book shape transparent housing. Intermittent flashing light illuminate the corner stopping tourist in their tracks. That's about it for Language of the Birds."]]

description:
In Indo-European religion, the behavior of birds has long been used for the purposes of divination by augurs. According to a suggestion by Walter Burkert, these customs may have their roots in the Paleolithic when, during the Ice Age, early humans looked for carrion by observing scavenging birds.[1]
There are also examples of contemporary bird-human communication and symbiosis. In North America, ravens have been known to lead wolves (and native hunters) to prey they otherwise would be unable to consume.[2][3]  In Africa, the greater honeyguide is known to guide humans to beehives in the hope that the hive will be incapacitated and opened for them.

name: Conservatory of Flowers
address: 100 John F Kennedy Dr, San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM']
reviews: [['Hayley Powers', 5, 'This place is so cool! it is not too big either which I think is great. You can really take time to see the various rooms without feeling exhausted. We went on a lovely sunny day so keep in mind the temp and humidity is such to keep very tropical plants thriving in here (so no jackets are needed!). Once you’re done I highly recommend sitting on the lawn with a blanket and having a picnic if the weather allows. The perfect afternoon in my opinion. Great place to take visitors.'], ['Brinda Guru', 5, 'This place is a plant lover’s paradise. The plants were maintained very well with separate temperature/humidity controlled areas. The highlight was the aquatic plants section with giant water lily. It was soothing and relaxing to spend time inside. You could also get some pictures here, they have setup benches with beautiful backgrounds.\n\nIf you are an SF resident, you have free access, and the lawn just outside the conservatory makes an amazing picnic spot!'], ['Dorena G.', 5, 'Stunning building and the indoors is lovely. The outdoor grounds are well manicured with many lovely outdoor flowering species. The ticket prices are very reasonable and you can pay a little extra to be able to enter the Japanese tea gardens and botanical gardens in Golden gate Park as well. The building is very old and has been well maintained over the decades. Different little annexes inside of different species of plants and micro climates. It is humid, so be prepared. It is a greenhouse after all.'], ['Domingo Magdaleno', 5, "It's home for me, for now."], ['Andrew Nagano', 4, "Although the conservatory has a cast variety of tropical plants, its orchid collection is extremely impressive ! Orchids everywhere - please looked up and on the tree branches and not only for orchids in pots because they are everywhere. Orchids of every size and shape and color..the only reason why I didn't give this a 5 star rating, is that I have been to other conservatories, albeit with smaller orchid collections, that have been free of charge to the public. But, this is a nice way to spend time in the city amongst beautiful plants in different climates."]]

description:
The Conservatory of Flowers is an elaborate Victorian greenhouse with a central dome rising nearly 60 feet (18 m) high and arch-shaped wings extending from it for an overall length of 240 feet (73 m). The building sits atop a gentle slope overlooking Conservatory Valley. The structural members are articulated through one predominant form, a four-centered or Tudor arch.
The Conservatory of Flowers consists of a wood structural skeleton with glass walls set on a raised masonry foundation. The entire structure has a shallow E-shaped plan that is oriented along an east-west axis. The central 60-foot (18 m) high pavilion is entered through a one-story, glassed-in vestibule with a gable roof on the south side of the pavilion. Flanking the rotunda to the east and west are one-story, symmetrical wings framed by wood arches. Each wing is L-shaped in plan, with cupolas adorning the intersection of the two segments.

[['Love Dove', 5, "This place is SPECTACULAR. So much to explore, aesthetically eye pleasing. Great atmosphere for all ages. It is handicap friendly, fun, exciting and something for every one.

Be ready to have your updated vaccinate/booster card ready and an ID to enter. The lines were not bad at all.

description:
Completely rebuilt in 2008, the Academy's primary building in Golden Gate Park covers 400,000 square feet (37,000 m2).[3][5] In early 2020, before the COVID-19 pandemic, the California Academy of Sciences had around 500 employees and an annual revenue of about $33 million.[2]
The California Academy of Sciences, California's oldest operating museum and research institution for the natural sciences, is governed by a forty-one member Board of Trustees[6] who are nominated and chosen by the California Academy of Sciences Fellows.  The Academy Fellows[7] are, in turn, "[n]ominated by their colleagues and appointed by the Board of Trustees...the Fellows remain members of the Fellowship for life."[8]  The Board of Trustees are then responsible for appointing the executive management of the Academy,[9] who in turn are responsible for overseeing the Academy's overall operation and the hiring of its other managers and employees.

name: Grace Cathedral
opening_hours: ['Monday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Julia Bennet', 5, 'One of the architecturally standout buildings in San Francisco with a large and unique stained glass window. Serene atmosphere within. Impressive programs to interest people. Walking the labyrinth there is a must have experience. They used to regularly host yoga classes on Tuesdays which were great. Location right at the top of nob hill makes it easy to walk down in any direction and still find yourself in some or the other iconic neighborhood in San Francisco. Lovely place.'], ['Daniel Brower', 5, 'A spectacular soaring Gothic Cathedral in California.
Grace Cathedral is a gem and an unusual cathedral for California.
It reminds one more of a Cathedral in Europe.
The stained glass is magnificent.  The music program is top notch.
The Evensong Service on Thursday evening is particularly beautiful and moving.'], ['IAN CHADWICK', 4, "It is very disappointing that Grace Cathedral is no longer hosting the Festival of Remember service, a tradition which goes back many decades. This wonderful, well attended event was co-hosted by the Royal Canadian Legion. It is a terrible shame that in that magnificent Cathedral, we are deprived of getting together and honoring the fallen who gave their lives during the two great wars. It was a very moving service. One can't imagine that the Reverend Alan Jones (who presided over the event for many years) would not have condoned the Cathedral's decision to cancel this event.
E. Ian Chadwick"], ['elviscilla2', 5, 'Beautiful on the outside, unfortunately it was closed when I arrived so I wasn’t able to see the interior.  I walked around the whole place. Nice benches for sitting in the courtyard. Nice lovely neighborhood with a nice dog park across from the east entrance.'], ['Ginger L', 5, 'I really enjoy visiting cathedrals and this one did not disappoint . If you arrive in the morning when the sun is coming in from the east you’ll enjoy an incredible light display from the stained glass windows . Beautiful architecture. A very peaceful experience . Free to visit']]

reviews: [['Amanda Ryan', 5, "We visiting the museum this Summer and enjoyed every second of the experience. My husband was the one who suggested it and I was unsure at first because I don't love photos as much as he does but my mind was quickly changed!! We had so much fun and had a lovely staff member from Ireland helping us out, Róisín who made the experience easy going and funny for us. I'll definitely recommend this place to fellow travellers and hope to visit on my next trip to San Fran again."], ['Megan Brophy', 5, 'Really enjoyed my experience at Museum of 3D Illusions San Fran. All staff were very welcoming and informative, especially Aisling. She was extremely helpful to us and made our experience a lot more fun. I would definitely recommend to friends!'], ['Aghna Nic Dhonnacha', 5, 'Visited the museum earlier this week and it was such great fun!! The photographer, Roisin who had a fabulous Irish accent, was super helpful and thanks to her we got some wonderful photos. name: Children's Creativity Museum
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: Closed', 'Wednesday: Closed', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 4:00 PM']
reviews: [['Danielle Brundige', 5, 'What a great place for children to use their own creativity and exercise their minds. My boys who are 3 and 5 loved it here! This museum is set up in stations and is not overwhelming.\n\nAlso loved they are a part of the Blue star museum program for military personnel! We will be back !'], ['Winnie x', 5, 'Great place with innovative design. It also has a great playground nearby. My son enjoyed it so much!'], ['Rondell Gibson', 4, 'Not for children under 3 or 4 in my opinion. Some of the stationed were closed when I went. There are place to eat near by and a good way to spend about 1 or 2 hrs with kids above 4. There are arts and craft stations, an audio and digital media area for those into creating videos and soundtracks.'], ['Shaun Correa', 3, 'For the price, this place was pretty disappointing. Most of the activities are relatively generic, and what our kid already experiences at her montessori daycare. Calling it a museum is a bit of a stretch. Good concept, and hope they develop further in the future.'], ['Neha Singh Tanwar', 5, "My kid doesn't want to leave. I don't want to leave because he is engaged. Little one loves it too. I have started loving the mystery box challenges myself. You see, this place is a gem for people with kids! With covid, things have changed but for good. I can take stroller inside. Everything is on first floor so very manageable with two kids."]]

name: Fort Funston
opening_hours: ['Monday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Thursday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Friday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Saturday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM', 'Sunday: 7:00 AM – 9:00 PM']
reviews: [['Matt Cronin', 5, 'Fort Funston is one of the underrated landscapes in and around SF proper. Really unique when you can see up and down the coast or if you can’t even see 10 feet in front of you in the fog. Incredible cliffs, nice vistas throughout, great for dogs, lots of walking paths, and occasionally you can even watch a local hang gliding club float around the coastline. It’s very peaceful, and it seems to be just enough off the beaten path.'], ['Joseph R', 5, 'Lots of Hawks and saw one 🦅 and a few vultures.'], ['Tony Wang', 5, 'Fort Funston has been a haven for us. We love taking our family here. It’s off-leash friendly with pretty paved roads. Would highly recommend coming here if you have a dog and want to be surrounded by nature.'], ['Basem Istanbouli', 5, "This is one of THE BEST places to see the bay area coast. It's pictures for days. So scenic. So photogenic. Truly a masterpiece of earth!\n\nThere's a lot of sand dunes and it can be a steep decline to get to the beach from the parking lot but if you follow the concrete trail out, there's an easier descent onto the beach."], ['John Hollar', 3, "Dog beach heaven! On our first visit I was impressed with how chill the dogs and owners were, both in the trails and on the beach. Dozens and dozens of off-leash dogs and absolutely no issues. The only thing holding this beach back is access to the water itself. There's only one trail down and it's *very* steep and sandy. Not accessible if you have any kind of mobility issue. Otherwise it's a great morning out, and at low tide the area to run and play in is vast!"]]

description:
The Fort was constructed upon windswept headlands along the Pacific coast and Ocean Beach below, above steep sandstone cliffs that provide a nesting habitat for a colony of bank swallows (Riparia riparia).  The last remnants of a  sand dune ecosystem that once covered the western half of San Francisco grows along the top of the headlands, with trailheads forming part of the California Coastal Trail that runs through San Francisco County.[1]
The land was acquired by the federal government in 1900 as the Lake Merced Military Reservation, originally intended to accommodate two 12-inch coast defense mortar batteries in the Coast Defenses of San Francisco (later Harbor Defenses). However, nothing significant was built there until after the American entry into World War I in early 1917. The fort, renamed for Major General Frederick Funston shortly after his death in 1917, began to take shape during World War I, with the construction of a parade ground, barracks and a series of coastal batteries. These were Battery Howe with four 12-inch mortars and Battery Bruff with two 5-inch M1900 guns on pedestal mounts. These weapons were relocated from Batteries McKinnon and Sherwood at Fort Winfield Scott, adjacent to the Presidio.[2][3] Battery Howe was named for Walter Howe, a general and veteran of the Indian wars who died in 1915. Battery Bruff was named after Lawrence Bruff, an Ordnance Corps colonel and instructor at West Point who died in 1911. In 1920 Battery Bruff was disarmed due to a withdrawal from Army service of the 5-inch gun.[2] In the early 1920s, Anti-aircraft Battery No. 5 of three 3-inch guns was built at the fort.[4]

reviews: [['Trishna Horvath', 5, "I am a member at The Asian Art Museum for a couple a reasons. One, I have a lifelong fascination with eastern philosophy and arts and The Asian Art Museum's presentations are well curated, intelligent, beautiful, and with a nice balance of ancient and contemporary.\nMy second reason is the cafe. Having a peaceful place in the middle of the city to sit and have tea, maybe get some work done, or enjoy a healthy meal is really wonderful. The cafe has been renovated recently and is called Sunday now. I had lunch there recently and it was great."], ['Danielle Rusthoven', 5, 'We loved the museum and the collections. Beautifully curated and the perfect size. Not too big or too small.. They have portable folding chairs to walk around with for those of us who may need it. The cafe was closed. The gift shop has some fun little treasures as well.'], ['Fırat Kart', 5, 'Continuity is a great event with room of relaxing music and visual show. Make sure you have a good device to capture photo/video in dark. With kids, if you arrive early checkout the event at entrance and let kids find their virtual drawing on wall. We had great day at the museum on a Sunday!!'], ['W. TRAVIS B.', 5, 'I still catch myself calling the Asian Art Museum the "Library" as that is originally what I knew it as. But it\'s been reincarnated as one of the most beautiful and interesting museums in the City. Probably my favorite. Definitely worth the effort. Paid parking across the street.'], ['Dalvin Josias', 5, 'This museum is extensive. The collection of art they have spans thousands of years and you can quite honestly stay there for hours and still not be able to get through everything. It’s an awesome curation of Asian and South East Asian art. I loved it and as a museum fanatic you will too.']]

name: Chinatown San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['KARTIK YADAV', 5, "Walking into Chinatown transports you into another country. Sidewalk signs and storefront names written in Chinese, along with Asian murals and Chinese lanterns strewn above. There's tons of shopping, items tightly packed into stores much cheaper than the tourist traps at the wharf. A wonderful time to window shop and find unique items. Everyone i encountered was so pleasant. As with most of San Fran, bring your walking shoes as parts are definitely on inclines."], ['Yrzd', 4, 'Felt like the businesses here were run by an older generation of Chinese immigrants. There is definitely less cultural orientation towards the Fresh-off-the-boat immigrant culture than towards a local culture featuring oriental China tourism ad westernized Bay Area fusion. Both of which are unique and inseparable from the immigration history of California.'], ['Lawrence', 5, "Amazing! A traditional and classic Chinatown that is fun to explore and doesn't feel too touristy, with actual Chinese folk living their lives in it. Plenty of murals, cool sights, and stores/restaurants.\n\nAn amazing place for Chinese-Americans to feel at home even when they are on the other side of the country, speaking as a New Yorker."], ['Geuvera Photography', 5, 'There is two areas: tourist zone and locals.  The best prices are in the local zone and the real food.  If your on a budget, this is where to go out to eat or have if you have taste.   The foodie and cultural haven that is as the original Chinatown States side is renown.  Try the dim sung.'], ['Lilly F', 5, 'Absolutely amazing! Beautiful and such a fun experience. We went here, walked around and got some delicious food. Would definitely recommend going here some time in your life, its absolutley worth it.']]

description: This is one of the oldest and most established Chinatowns in the U.S. Beyond iconic Dragon’s Gate, a bustling maze of streets and alleys brims with dim sum joints and other traditional eateries. Also found are herbalists, bakeries, souvenir shops, and dark cocktail lounges and karaoke bars. There are ornate temples, including the landmark Tien How, as well as the Chinese Historical Society of America Museum.https://www.google.com/search?q=Chinatown+San+Francisco&as_epq=&as_oq=&as_eq=&as_nlo=&as_nhi=&lr=lang_en&cr=&as_qdr=all&as_sitesearch=&as_occt=any&safe=images&as_filetype=&tbs=

name: Mosaic Stairway
address: Moraga St &, Moraga Steps, San Francisco
opening_hours: ['Monday: Open 24 hours', 'Tuesday: Open 24 hours', 'Wednesday: Open 24 hours', 'Thursday: Open 24 hours', 'Friday: Open 24 hours', 'Saturday: Open 24 hours', 'Sunday: Open 24 hours']
reviews: [['Jesse Walker', 5, 'Lots of fun. We showed up right at daybreak early morning and no one was around. Made for some awesome photos.'], ['Silly Bunny', 5, 'There were three sets of stairs from the very bottom to the very top. The bottom set is the one with the colorful art with gardens on both sides. When we walked up to the top, we could see the city very clearly. It was quite foggy at the time, unfortunately.'], ['Shum Fong', 5, 'Artistically created by using thousands of mosaic on few hundreds of steps, it is a work of art! Great for photo taking'], ['Siddharth Reddy', 5, 'One of the most scenic and photo worthy spot in San Francisco. Always beautiful serene and magical.'], ['Venkatesh Rao', 5, 'Low crowd. Enjoyed climbing the stairs in cool weather with the fog misting in.']]

description:
The hill on which the park lies is composed primarily of sand and San Francisco chert, formed in the Mesozoic era. The layout of the park uses the steepness of the hill to good advantage, offering good views of the city (particularly to the north).
At the peak of the park is a small lawn. Notable views are available from various lookouts lower down, including "The Window," an overlook on the western side of the hill from which there is a sweeping vista of Golden Gate Park, the Pacific Ocean, and, on clear days, northward up the coast to the white cliffs of Drake's Bay.

name: Lombard Street
opening_hours: Opening hours unkown
reviews: [['Siju K J', 5, 'A great place to visit. Marvelous design. Great views. If you are planning to visit by walk use tram. Otherwise please be ready to climb steep road almost 27 degree steep. For elderly better visit using tram or travel by car. Great opportunities for photography and must place to visit. Place is very clean and well organized. Once you come out of the street, you can find restaurants near by.'], ['Ana Khatchiperadze', 5, 'This street is famous because it is the most crooked street in the world. But also it is very beautiful. Summer and spring time is the best time to visit this place, while flowers are blooming. There are stairs that go all the way down. There you will see beautifully painted houses with beautiful doors. And everything in plants and flowers. I think this is one of the must see places in San Francisco.'], ['Zahra Kent', 5, "I'm from Florida, totally flatland. Made this drive without any issues. If you are nervous, don't be. It was much less scary than you expect to drive down. It's easier than tight parking garages. Kids thought it was fun. Next time I'd have them walk down and race the car. There are nice sidewalks. It's really pretty. Beautiful views of the bay from that area. It's a quick visit, plan no more than 20 minutes. We found great parking at the bottom to get out and take some photos after driving down."], ['Joel Twentyman', 3, 'Unusual quirky winding street which has now obtained iconic status in San Francisco and almost certainly a "must see" for visitors to the city. The red bricked surface paving and bordering greenery gives it a charming, almost surreal appearance. Of course popular with motorists and pedestrians wishing to experience navigating and enjoying the wonderful views from this famous location. Especially romantic at night with the lights of "downtown" twinkling in the distance.'], ['Goesto Restaurants', 5, "It was very pretty with the flowers blooming. We tried to drive down this street, oh man was that an adventure. You can't go more than like 5 miles an hour and must watch for tourists! Couldn't really take a great picture from the car due to absolute fear slowly inching down but definitely looks unique and colorful when looking at it from the bottom. These bumpy concrete slides ...https://www.google.com/search?q=Concrete+Slides&as_epq=&as_oq=&as_eq=&as_nlo=&as_nhi=&lr=lang_en&cr=&as_qdr=all&as_sitesearch=&as_occt=any&safe=images&as_filetype=&tbs=

name: The Palace Of Fine Arts
opening_hours: ['Monday: Closed', 'Tuesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Thursday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Friday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Saturday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM', 'Sunday: 10:00 AM – 5:00 PM']
reviews:
[['Ajay Mohan', 5, "The wonderful hilly roads leading to The Palace of Fine Arts already provide a glimpse of what's in store. This place has different entry points all around the place. Various different sculptures, statues, towering pillars and water bodies around the place perfectly compliment each other and totally justifying it's name. This not only reminds us of the past but with a bit of help from weather gods acts as a perfect setting for photography enthusiasts. If you want to spend a quality family time please do consider to visit The Palace of Fine Arts.
There are designated parking lots around the place but otherwise also plenty of roadside lots available."], ['Dylan G', 5, 'Incredible place to walk around at night. Very romantic.  Lots of instgramers and tourists at all hours of the day, but that is to be expected.  The Palace itself has been home to everything from museum exhibits to real life tech accelerators.  It’s an interesting place with an interesting history.

The Palace is also near to Chrissy field as well and you can even walk/jog along the beaches and across the Golden Gate Bridge if you’re up for 3-4 mile hike.'], ['Nick-Anthony Zamucen', 5, 'This is where I married my beautiful wife Molly 11 yrs ago. It was a beautiful unforgettable SF wedding. We were married under the rotunda on a warm October afternoon. Three kids later and a million new memories, but that warm October day is still one of my most fondest. (PS)'], ['Kayta Giles', 5, 'I like this place thanks to Christian  Strauss for sharing this.'], ['Kyle Kempf', 5, "A phenomenal park with a gorgeous rotunda. It's busy nearly every hour of the day but I never had trouble finding parking in the surrounding area. reviews:
[['Colyer Dupont', 5, 'History buff heaven! It even goes out under its own power sometimes on some holidays. Those events aren’t cheap but general entry to explore the ship is.'], ['wayne crawford', 5, "Amazing floating museum!! Massive kudos to Linda and the whole team here, their passion and hard work to preserve the history and knowledge surrounding this epic piece of history shines as soon as you speak to them.
Self guided tour was clearly outlined in the program provided. Price of admission is very reasonable at $20 ($15) for students. There's no time limit, in fact there's so much to see and learn about it's best to take your time. Working guns allow you to manipulate actual artillery (not loaded obviously).
Accurate dioramas show the scenario at omaha beach of which this ship was part of.
Can't recommend this enough for all ages!"], ['Justin Bradley', 5, 'Engine room and the engine itself is just.... breathtaking for for any amateur or professional home tinkerers. Rest of the ship is great as well. The group take pride in keeping this thing clean and in working order.'], ['Brandon Evans', 5, "This ship is still operational and goes out periodically for events.  The tour is self guided and you are free to wander about the ship in any area that isn't chained off. The museum portion has a lot of interesting information regarding the use of the cargo ships during and after the war.  We were able to go down in the engine room and the engineer was available to answer questions about running the ship."], ['KFC Guy', 4, "I visited this iconic old ship as I was interested to see what an old Liberty ship was like.  It was amazing to see the old lady and I felt like I was looking at a bit of history.  The engine room was incredibly complicated and how they built that so quickly I really don't know!"]]

description:
SS Jeremiah O'Brien is a Liberty ship built during World War II and named after the American Revolutionary War ship captain Jeremiah O'Brien (1744–1818).She is Known for her Three Cylinder Triple expansion steam engine And Known for the footage for James Cameron's Titanic
Now based in San Francisco, she is a rare survivor[a] of the 6,939-ship 6 June 1944 D-Day armada off the coast of Normandy, France.[5]

name: Grandview Park
opening_hours: ['Monday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Tuesday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Wednesday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Thursday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Friday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Saturday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM', 'Sunday: 5:00 AM – 12:00 AM']
reviews: [['Rita Deleuse', 5, 'This is one of the most beautiful San Francisco views. You can see 360 degrees around.  There are alot of stairs to get up there but well worth it. Usually not too crowded. Definitely a local gem!!'], ['Rick Crisostomo', 5, "A hidden gem. Lives up to its name, grand view. It's a teeny hill, but u get a great view of northern SF...from downtown to ocean beach. Twin Peaks blocks the eastern view of SF, but I watched the sunrise on Grandview park, and the sun rising behind twin peaks was spectacular. I can imagine this is also a good spot to watch the sun set here too because u get a overhead view of ocean beach/outer Sunset."], ['Obie Tric', 5, 'Beautiful unprecedented views of the ocean and city below. From the golden gate park to downtown. The stairs on the west side are very unique and make for a quick trip to the 16th street mural steps. The views are phenomenal!! There is a lower ring below the top where everyone goes and it’s the best spot!!'], ['Luca Fox', 5, 'Excellent sunset spot (if Karl’s not around). It’s pretty exposed so it can get both windy and foggy up there. If you want a bit of a walk, take the 16th Avenue Tiled Steps to or from here - they’re just below the park on the western side.'], ['Michael Bass', 5, 'Sweeping views from this park — giving shape to the incredible width of Golden Gate Park and dimensionality to the city as a whole. You learn why the Sunset District really gets its name, as the sun blankets and then darkens the entire neighborhood in a span of 30 minutes.']]

description:
Despite its small size, 3.98 acres (1.61 ha) or about the size of a city block, the park is important geologically and botanically and offers views of downtown San Francisco, Golden Gate Park, to the Pacific Ocean, the Marin headlands, and across to the Sutro Tower.
The summit of Grandview Park rises to about 666 feet (203 m).[3] It is an outcrop of chert, which is part of the heterogeneous assemblage known as the Franciscan Formation, or Franciscan Assemblage, the primary geologic feature on which the city of San Francisco is founded, here covered with a thin layer of sand. It provides one of the last remaining habitats within the city for a number of native plants, including the endangered Franciscan wallflower and dune tansy, and also bush lupin, beach strawberry, bush monkey flower, and coyote bush. The hill is crowned with Monterey cypress trees.

name: Muir Woods National Monument
opening_hours: ['Monday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Tuesday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Wednesday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Thursday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Friday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Saturday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM', 'Sunday: 8:00 AM – 8:00 PM']
reviews:
[['AJ Baxter', 5, "I cannot describe how amazing seeing the redwoods was!  Wow! Easy path or you can be more adventurous. In and out of shade and dappled sunlight.

The staff was so so helpful. The ranger at the entry shop was so kind to help me get just the right passport for this and more adventures.

Can't wait to use my National Park Pass again!"], ['Ebony Damis-Salaam', 5, 'My sister and I had a wonderful time. This is definitely a kid friendly activity. The peace and beauty that surrounds you is surreal. I will definitely be going back. The road to get there is very winding and slightly unnerving but totally worth it. The views are stunning. The trails are clean and well kept. They have several places to sit and relax. I would recommend this place any day. It is very cool in the mornings and the trees provide great shade but it stays cool for a while.'], ['Kat Johnson', 5, "Reservations for parking need to be purchased online beforehand. Time slots fill up quickly so plan ahead!
There's also a shuttle service but we didn't use it.

This park is absolutely stunning. Clean, marked trails with historic and educational markers throughout and the raw nature within is well worth any of the costs. I can't wait to go back."], ['Travis Hollowell', 3, 'The redwoods are impressive and the wooden path through the woods is well kept and clean. Bathrooms were decent and well placed both before and after the entrance. We paid in advance for parking a month in advance and despite arriving fairly soon after opening, had to park far away in their second overflow lot. Despite that, the size of the crowd was well managed by the timed entry tickets.'], ['Jared Warmack', 5, "Definitely worth a little traffic and some precarious twists and turns to see this place. There is a great selection of hikes to choose from depending on your challenge level and stamina. You're going to see some awesome trees, some of which were seeded before the fall of the Roman Empire. On a quiet day this place would be awesome for bird watchers, but even on a busy day, a lot of the birds are tame enough that they aren't bothered by the people walking by."]]

description:
Muir Woods National Monument is a United States National Monument managed by the National Park Service, named after naturalist John Muir. It is located on Mount Tamalpais near the Pacific coast, in southwestern Marin County, California. It is part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area, and is 12 miles (19 km) north of San Francisco. It protects 554 acres (224 ha),[4] of which 240 acres (97 ha) are old growth coast redwood (Sequoia sempervirens) forests,[5] one of a few such stands remaining in the San Francisco Bay Area.
The Muir Woods National Monument is an old-growth coastal redwood forest.[6] Due to its proximity to the Pacific Ocean, the forest is regularly shrouded in a coastal marine layer fog, contributing to a wet environment that encourages vigorous plant growth. The fog is also vital for the growth of the redwoods as they use moisture from the fog during droughty seasons, in particular the dry summer.[7]

description:
The Contemporary Jewish Museum was founded in 1984 and was housed in a small gallery space near San Francisco's waterfront for over two decades. In 1989, the museum initiated a planning process to address the growing community need for its programs. The result was the decision to create a more expansive and centrally located facility with increased exhibitions, an area dedicated to education, and added program areas including live music, theater, dance, literary events, and film. In June 2008, the museum opened a new 63,000 square-foot facility in downtown San Francisco.
The museum has no permanent collection. It curates and hosts a broad array of exhibitions each year in collaboration with other institutions.
